(1078, 2, 0, '', 'From Sage Pubs', 0, 1, 1, 'The goal of transition services is to improve the postschool outcomes for students with disabilities, but more than 10 years after the Individuals with Disabilities Act (IDEA) mandated transition services, students with disabilities are still exiting high school with significantly different postschool outcomes than their peers. Community-based instruction, work experience, family involvement, interagency collaboration, and postsecondary training have been highlighted as methods to improve student outcomes. This article identifies 101 community-based transition programs that incorporate community-based instruction, work experience, and postsecondary education especially designed for students aged 18-21 years old. Findings regarding disability populations, ages served, community locations, funding sources, interagency collaboration, and staffing of these programs are discussed.', '2009-05-07 10:12:23', '', 'Status of community-based transition programs: A national database', 1002, 'Career Development of Exceptional Individuals', '0885-7288', '27', '2', '', '', '', '2004', '', 0, 0, 0, 131, 149, 0, '', '', '', '10.1177/088572880402700202', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Gaumer, A. S., Morningstar, M. E., & Clark, G. M. (2004). Status of community-based transition programs: A national database. <I>Career Development for Exceptional Individuals, 27(2), </I> 131-149. 10.1177/088572880402700202', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;4;6', '2;3;4;7;11'),
(1079, 13, 0, '', 'STEPS Forward: Inclusive Post-secondary Education for Young Adults with\r\nIntellectual Disabilities', 0, 0, 1, 'In Canada, the struggle for people with intellectual disabilities to gain recognition as citizens and to be included in the mainstream has gone on for more than 30 years (Wolfsenberger, 1980; Brown & Smith, 1992). For the past 10 years, the Canadian government and advocates for persons with intellectual disabilities have shifted their efforts from appeals and legislation on the basis of human rights in favour of an emphasis on full citizenship for members of this systemically excluded segment of the population. \r\n\r\nHigher education and the workplace are two key entry points into full inclusion in civil society. Barriers to entering the post-secondary system reinforce the othering of persons with disabilities (Slee, 2000) as to artificial, segregated post-secondary programmes that deny people with intellectual disabilities the normal transitions into adulthood and participation as citizens taken for granted by most (Uditsky et al, 1988). \r\n\r\nUnlike its neighbouring province, Alberta, which has inclusive post-secondary education (IPSE) in place for nearly 20 years, British Columbia is a relative latecomer. The first IPSE initiative was started in 2002 and in 2005 only a dozen or so students have been permitted access to post-secondary education, under the auspices of the STEPS Forward Inclusive Post-secondary Education Society (STEPS). \r\n\r\nThis paper will briefly report on existing research into the inclusion of young adults with intellectual disabilities into the campus mainstream, including the experience of Alberta and other jurisdictions. STEPSâ€™ philosophy of inclusion and its academic and co-op work components will be described as background.', '2009-05-07 10:22:52', '', 'STEPS Forward: Inclusive post-secondary education for young adults with intellectual disabilities', 0, '', '', '2005', '', '', '', '', '2005', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Steps_Forward_Inclusive_Post_Secondary_Education_for_Young_Adults_with_Intellectual_Disabilities', 'Steps Ahead', 'http://www.steps-forward.org/Steps_Forward_Inclusive_Post_Secondary_Education_for_Young_Adults_with_Intellectual_Disabilities.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'Greenholtz, J., Mosoff, J., & Hurtado, T. (2005). <I>STEPS Forward: Inclusive post-secondary education for young adults with intellectual disabilities.</I> Retrieved June 12, 2009 from Steps Ahead Web site: http://www.steps-forward.org/Steps_Forward_Inclusive_Post_Secondary_Education_for_Young_Adults_with_Intellectual_Disabilities.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;6', '2;4;5;7;11'),
(1080, 5, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'Told through the eyes of a journalist and college staff, this article describes the college life of Katie Apostolides, a young adult with Down syndrome who is participating in a fully inclusive college experience.  She gained admission to Becker College in Massachusetts through regular admission, and lives on campus in the dorms.  The article explores a variety of perceptions regarding the benefits, barriers, and challenges of postsecondary education for persons with disabilities.  A limitation of this article is that Katie Apostolidesâ€™s views and analysis are marginally represented.  The article proposes linkages between her successes in college, and the role of intensive intervention services during Apostolidesâ€™s childhood.  Katie Apostolidesâ€™s mother challenged conventional conceptions of her daughterâ€™s potential and ensured her access to inclusive education and intensive educational and therapeutic services.', '2009-05-07 10:34:42', '', 'A dream not denied: â€˜Just a normal girlâ€™', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2006', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 'New Tork Times Education', 'http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/05/education/edlife/downs.html? R=1', '', '2006', '11', '5', '2009', '2', '27', 1, 0, '', '', 'Kaufman, L. (2006). A dream not denied: â€˜Just a normal girlâ€™. <I>New York Times Online</I> Retrieved February 27, 2009, from http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/05/education/edlife/downs.html? R=1', '', '', '', '2;6', '5;7'),
(1081, 13, 0, '', 'Literature Review', 0, 0, 1, 'Review of the literature prepared for the New Zealand National Advisory Committee on Health and Disability to inform its project on services for adults with an intellectual disability. This review contains two distinct but interrelated sections. The first section contained in this review is Transition and Young Adults with an Intellectual Disability. The second section included is titled Adult Education for Adults with an Intellectual Disability. \r\n The first section of this review is focused on young people with an intellectual disability and the transition into adulthood. While previous reviews conducted for the purposes of this National Health Committee Project (New Zealand) have focused on adults with an intellectual disability, transition planning and issues related to this process generally begin to occur during the secondary school years. For this reason, the section of the review of Transition contains information relating to young people under the age of 21 years (the age to which high school education in New Zealand for young people with an intellectual disability can be provided).The second section of the review explores the area of Adult Education for Adults with an Intellectual Disability. Opportunity for further education is one aspect of transition and transition related planning therefore links between the two areas are highlighted where relevant.', '2009-05-07 10:59:18', '', 'Education for adults with an intellectual disability (including transition to adulthood)', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2003', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Education+(FinalVersion)7', 'NZ: National Health Committee', 'http://www.nhc.health.govt.nz/moh.nsf/pagescm/711/$File/Education+(FinalVersion)7.pdf', 'ISBN (Document): 0-478-25323-0', '2003', '15', '', '2009', '3', '24', 0, 0, '', '', 'Mirfin-Veitch, B. (2003). <I>Education for adults with an intellectual disability (including transition to adulthood).</I> Auckland, NZ: National Advisory Committee on Health and Disability. Retrieved March 24, 2009, from New Zealand National Health Committee Web site: http://www.nhc.health.govt.nz/moh.nsf/pagescm/711/$File/Education+(FinalVersion)7.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;6', '4;5;10'),
(1082, 13, 4, '', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Education Supports,\r\nResearch Findings Brief , study area 4a, volume 11', 0, 0, 1, 'In an effort to better understand the services and accommodations that can lead to improvements in student retention, completion, or entrance to a four year college program, this brief reports on a study of the accommodations offered to student with significant disabilities participating in community college coursework in Massachusetts. The purpose of the study is to identify the current nature of support and services.  An overview of the methods, findings and implications are presented.', '2009-05-07 11:13:09', '', 'Topical review â€“ A state profile of current practices in community colleges for students with significant disabilities', 0, '', '', '11', '', '', '', '', '2000', '1', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'NCSPES 082-H01', 'Rehabilitation Research & Training Center', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase1/082-H01.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '7', 0, 0, '', '', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Education Supports (2000). <I>Topical review â€“ A state profile of current practices in community colleges for students with significant disabilities.</I> Honolulu, HI: University of Hawaiâ€˜I at Manoa Rehabilitation Research & Training Center. Retrieved June 7, 2009, from University of Hawaii at Manoa Web site: http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase1/082-H01.pdf', '', '', '', '1;4;6', '1;5;7;9'),
(1083, 13, 0, '', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Education Supports (2002). â€œPreparation for and Support of Youth with COGNITIVE DISABILITIES in Postsecondary Educationâ€\r\nProceedings of the second summit of the coalition for the support of individuals with significant disabilities in postsecondary education. Research and Rehabilitation Training Center, University of Hawaii at Manoa.\r\nHttp://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/proceedings/BostonSummitProceedings.pdf', 0, 0, 0, 'This document reports on the proceedings of the Second Summit: Preparation for and Support of Youth with Cognitive Disabilities in Postsecondary Education. The Second Summit was held in Boston, Massachusetts at the Institute for Community Inclusion. It was a gathering of people interested in supporting youth with significant cognitive disabilities in postsecondary education. Participants included consumers, family members, professionals, and policy makers. The Second Summit of the Coalition for the Support of individuals with Significant Disabilities in Postsecondary Education, was sponsored by the Administration on Developmental Disabilities (ADD), the National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Education Supports (NCSPES), University of Hawaiâ€˜i at Manoa, the National Center on Secondary Education and Transition (NCSET), University of Minnesota, the Institute for Community Inclusion (ICI), the University of Massachusetts at Boston, and TASH. The purpose of the Second Summit was to increase the awareness and understanding of supports and services for students with significant cognitive disabilities in postsecondary education. The intended goal was for participants to learn how to access and best use the provisions in place. The focuses were three: first, the students and what college attendance means to them; second, the professors and what they have done to assist the students in being successful; and finally, the families and their hopes and goals for their student in postsecondary education.', '2009-05-07 11:35:22', '', 'Proceedings of the second summit of the coalition for the support of individuals with significant disabilities in postsecondary education', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2002', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'BostonSummitProceedings', 'Research and Rehabilitation Training Center, University of Hawaii at Manoa', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/proceedings/BostonSummitProceedings.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '17', 0, 0, '', '', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Education Supports (2002). <I>â€œPreparation for and Support of Youth with COGNITIVE DISABILITIES in Postsecondary Educationâ€ Proceedings of the second summit of the coalition for the support of individuals with significant disabilities in postsecondary education.</I> Honolulu, HI: University of Hawaiâ€˜i at Manoa Rehabilitation Research & Training Center. Retrieved February 17, 2009, from University of Hawaii at Manoa Web site: http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/proceedings/BostonSummitProceedings.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;4;5;6', '2;4;5;7;10'),
(1084, 13, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'Describes the activities of NDSS to remove access barriers for individuals with intellectual disabilities who wish to pursue postsecondary education. Funding opportunities, changes to the Higher Education Opportunity Act, and new programs at The College of New Jersey College, Mercer County Community College, University of South Carolina, Columbia, and Clemson University  are discussed.', '2009-05-07 11:50:13', '', 'NDSS transition and post secondary education initiative overview', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'pdf ndss transitionandpostsecondaryeducationinitiativeoverview', 'National Down Syndrome Society', 'http://www.ndss.org/images/stories/NDSSresources/pdfs/pdf ndss transitionandpostsecondaryeducationinitiativeoverview.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '4', '29', 0, 0, '', '', 'National Down Syndrome Society (2009). <I>NDSS transition and post secondary education initiative overview.</T> Retrieved 4/29/09 from http://www.ndss.org/images/stories/NDSSresources/pdfs/pdf%20ndss%20transitionandpostsecondaryeducationinitiativeoverview.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '2;5;7'),
(1086, 13, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'This issue highlights sample programs and services that provide non-academic, non-degree postsecondary options for individuals with developmental disabilities. Highlighted programs include Goodwill Industries, University Affiliated Programs (UAPs), as well as regional and local community programs and services.', '2009-05-07 15:32:21', '', 'Pathways to employment: Non-degree postsecondary options for individuals with disabilities (Part II)', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2000', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 4, 0, 'non_degree_postsec_2', 'Heath Resource Center at GW University', 'http://www.heath.gwu.edu/files/active/non_degree_postsec_2.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '27', 0, 0, '', '', 'Payne, M. (2000). <I>Pathways to employment: Non-degree postsecondary options for individuals with disabilities (Part II).</I> Washington, DC: George Washington University HEATH Resource Center. Retrieved February 27, 2009, from George Washington University Web site: http://www.heath.gwu.edu/files/active/non_degree_postsec_2.pdf', '', '', '', '2;5;6', '5;7;11'),
(1087, 1, 0, '', 'ISBN - 1-895070-63-5', 0, 1, 0, 'This report presents the findings from a study of current initiatives to include persons with disabilities in postsecondary education in Canada.  The study surveyed 40 community college educators, and interviewed 35 teachers and parents. The study seeks to identify the barriers to successful inclusion, the factors contributing to successful inclusion, and the factors facilitating the transition from postsecondary education to employment. The author suggests program components that will improve teachers and administrators support of postsecondary education for students with intellectual disabilities. These components include: support networks for teachers, in-service instruction by community agencies, disability awareness workshops, professional development, and a team approach to individualized programming and accommodations.', '2009-05-07 15:51:18', 'Building bridges: Inclusive postsecondary education for people with intellectual disabilities', '', 0, '', 'ISBN - 1-895070-63-5', '', '', '', '', '', '1996', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN - 1-895070-63-5', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'The Roeher Institute.. (1996). <I>Building bridges: Inclusive postsecondary education for people with intellectual disabilities.</I> North York, ON: The Roeher Institute.', '', 'The Roeher Institute', 'New York (Ontario)', '', '1;4;6', '2;5;7;11'),
(1088, 13, 6, '', 'ERIC# ED390200\r\nDigital conversion from microfiche', 0, 0, 1, 'This literature review examines the American and Canadian educational research and program literature related to the inclusion of adults with intellectual disabilities in the postsecondary community college system and adult vocational training systems and has the overall goal of identifying factors that contribute to effective integration. Following an introduction which identifies themes of research in this area, the second chapter looks at current levels of participation across disabilities, by disability category, and specifically for people with an intellectual disability. The next section presents data on the impact of participation in postsecondary education on patterns of employment. The issue of integrated versus segregated education is addressed next, followed by a section on barriers to participation including the legal and policy framework, institutional policies, classroom practices, and personal factors. Specific success factors are identified in the sixth section, including legal/policy factors, institutional factors, and classroom factors. The seventh section describes the Integrated Access Model. The final section describes specific programs in Canada and the United States. A conclusion notes that the small body of existing literature indicates clear benefits to inclusion, provided there is adequate support and sufficient planning.', '2009-05-07 16:02:28', '', 'Inclusion of individuals with disabilities in post-secondary education: A review of the literature', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1995', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 41, 0, 'Ticoll 8d', 'ERIC', 'http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/14/4d/8d.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '27', 0, 0, '', '', 'Ticoll, M. (1995). <I>Inclusion of individuals with disabilities in post-secondary education: A review of the literature.</I> Retrieved February 27, 2009, from ERIC database: http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/14/4d/8d.pdf', '', '', '', '1;3;4', '4;5;6;7;9;10;11'),
(1089, 1, 0, '3', 'In Blaine and Others book Alternative futures for the education of students with severe disabilities. \r\nISBN-0-88864-936-3\r\nOnline version available.', 0, 1, 1, 'The paper describes the On Campus Program at the University of Alberta, which serves 11 students with moderate to significant disabilities in a university setting. Students have Individual Integration Plans, which identify and organize a set of university-based activities appropriate to the needs, interests, and strengths of each student. Activities include classes, recreational activities, and social interactions. The program was developed based on 14 positive assumptions, including: generic setting, integrated activities, philosophy of life-long learning, enhanced self-esteem, wide variety of life-enriching experiences, improved employment possibilities, normative and challenging expectations, and opportunities for numerous associations and connections.', '2009-05-07 16:09:50', 'Alternative futures for the education of students with severe disabilities', 'On campus: Integrating the university environment', 0, '', '0-88864-936-3', '', '', '', '', '', '1988', '', 0, 0, 0, 764, 782, 0, '', 'ERIC', 'http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/1f/61/db.pdf#', 'ISBN-0-88864-936-3', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '27', 1, 0, '', 'Uditsky, B., Frank, S., Hart, L., & Jefferey, S. (1988). On campus: Integrating the university environment. In Baine, D., Sobsey, D., Wilgosh, L., & Kysela, G. (eds.). <I>Alternative futures for the education of students with severe disabilities</I>(pp. 97-103). Edmonton: University of Alberta.', '', 'University of Alberta', 'Edmonton', '', '1;2;6', '5;7;11'),
(1090, 3, 0, '', ' Published Online: March 13, 2009\r\nPublished in Print: March 18, 2009\r\n\r\nAvailable to subscribers free. $2.95 article purchase fee.', 0, 1, 1, 'This article presents an overview of some of the current barriers to postsecondary education for individuals with autism or intellectual disabilities. The article includes the personal experiences of parents who fought diligently to secure their transition age childrenâ€™s rights to self-determination and access to post secondary education. Themes include the absence of agency support for youthsâ€™ postsecondary goals, the importance of self-determined transition planning, and the potential uses of the â€œsummary of performanceâ€ documents.', '2009-05-08 03:50:40', '', 'Charting a course after high school', 0, '', 'ISSN: 0277-4232', '', '', '', '', '', '2009', '3', 18, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 'Education Week', 'http://www.edweek.org/login.html?source=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2009/03/18/25transitions.h28.html&destination=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2009/03/18/25transitions.h28.html&levelId=2100', '', '2009', '3', '13', '2009', '2', '27', 0, 0, '', '', 'Samuels, C. A. (2009). Charting a course after high school. [Electronic version].<I>Education Week</I> Retrieved February 27, 2009, from http://www.edweek.org/login.html?source=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2009/03/18/25transitions.h28.html&destination=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2009/03/18/25transitions.h28.html&levelId=2100', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '4;5;7;10;12'),
(1091, 5, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'This article reports on several educational programs provided by colleges and universities in the U.S. for students with intellectual disabilities. Profiles include Strive University offered at the University of Southern Maine in Portland, the Single Step Childcare Program at the Community College of Baltimore County in Dundalk, Maryland, the Transition to Independent Living Program of the Taft College in California, and a program at George Mason University. The article includes interviews representing a range of perspectives, some of which are openly skeptical or critical of postsecondary educational opportunities for individuals with intellectual disabilities.', '2009-05-08 04:06:40', 'Chronicle of Higher Education, The', 'From special ed to higher ed', 0, '', '0009-5982', '51', '24', '', '', '', '2005', '10', 18, 0, 0, 1, 6, 0, '', 'Steps Forward', 'http://stepsforward.homestead.com/From_Special_Ed_to_Higher_Ed.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '27', 0, 0, '', '', 'Schmidt, P. (2005). <I>From special ed to higher ed. Chronicle of Higher Education, 51(24), 1-6.</I> Retrived February 27, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://stepsforward.homestead.com/From_Special_Ed_to_Higher_Ed.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '4;5;7'),
(1092, 13, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'The primary purpose of interagency transition teams serving youth with disabilities is to improve the post school outcomes for youth who are transitioning from secondary education to adult life. This resource is published to assist state-level transition coordinators as well as for persons charged with the responsibility of forming, conducting, and evaluating the performance of interagency transition teams serving youth with disabilities. This resource is appropriate for a diverse group of stakeholders, including state education agency transition coordinators,  the department of vocational rehabilitation, the departments of health and human services, parents, postsecondary education institutions, and advocates.', '2009-05-08 04:16:37', '', 'Essential tools: Interagency transition team development and facilitation', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2005', '12', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Stodden Brown Galloway', 'ERIC', 'http://eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/1b/a2/18.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '14', 0, 0, '', '', 'Stodden, R. A., Brown, S. E., Galloway, L. M., Mzarek, S. & Noy, L. (2005). <I>Essential tools: Interagency transition team development and facilitation.</I> Minneapolis, MN: University of Minnesota, Institute on Community Integration, National Center on Secondary Education and Transition. Retrieved June 14, 2009, from ERIC database: http://eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/1b/a2/18.pdf', 'University of Minnesota, Institute on Community Integration, National Center on Secondary Education and Transition.', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '3;4;10'),
(1093, 2, 0, '', 'for Purchase from Emerald Publishing Group', 0, 1, 1, 'Purpose - The purpose of the research reported in this paper was to examine the type of adjustments to delivery appropriate for students with an autistic spectrum disorder in a UK higher education setting. Design/methodology/approach - A case study in a UK university was conducted over a two-year period. Findings - A variety of adjustments may be required for students with an autistic spectrum disorder in a UK higher education environment, including adjustments to teaching delivery, assessment and pastoral care. Research limitations/implications - Although the case study reported in this paper focused on just three students with an autistic spectrum disorder, the number of students entering UK higher education with such disorders is likely to increase and institutions need to be aware of the adjustments that may potentially be required.', '2009-05-08 05:10:48', '', 'Teaching students with autistic spectrum disorders in HE', 1007, 'Education + Training', '0040-0912', '47', '7', '', '', '', '2005', '', 0, 0, 0, 484, 495, 0, 'Taylor 2005', 'Emerald Publishing Group', 'http://www.emeraldinsight.com/10.1108/00400910510626330', '10.1108/00400910510626330', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Taylor, M. J. (2005). Teaching students with autistic spectrum disorders in HE. <I>Education + Training, 47(7), </I> 484-495.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '6;7;9'),
(1094, 1, 0, '', 'ISBN: 1557669104', 0, 1, 0, 'The principles of universal design for learning (UDL) emphasize the presentation of information in multiple formats and media. This guidebook reveals how educators and transition specialists can apply the principles of UTL to help students in transition achieve their academic aspirations and make decisions about their future. Coining this approach Universal Design for Transition (UDT), the authors provide guidance on how to apply UDT strategies towards enhancing studentsâ€™ self-determination skills, planning comprehensive strengths and needs assessments, tailoring IEPâ€™s to the studentâ€™s goals and interests, and preparing students for career and postsecondary options. The text includes a chapter by Donald Finn & Jennifer Watson Klein entitled â€œUniversal Design for Transition and Postsecondary Educationâ€.', '2009-05-08 05:33:13', 'Universal design for transition: A roadmap for planning and instruction', '', 0, '', '1557669104', '', '', '1', '', '', '2009', '12', 9, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN: 1557669104', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Thoma, C. A., Bartholomew, C. C., & LaRon, A. S. (2009). <I>Universal design for transition: A roadmap for planning and instruction</I>. Baltimore, MD: Paul H. Brookes.', '', 'Paul H. Brookes', 'Baltimore', 'MD', '1;2', '4;7;8;12'),
(1095, 8, 5, '', 'Given at 7th annual second city conference on disability studies in education', 0, 0, 1, 'This paper explores how the civil rights of students with developmental disabilities and the moral and practical application of those rights challenges the Supreme Court of Canada relativist analysis of the rights of individuals with disabilities. While debate continues over which students with developmental disabilities can be included, when and under whose authority, students with significant developmental disabilities have been included in universities, colleges and technical institutes for over 20 years. A right to education exists for children with disabilities but not a right to an inclusive education, the same individuals who may be denied an inclusive education as children are being fully included in elite academic post-secondary institutions for which there is no legal right. This apparent contradiction offers constructive and substantive insights into the nature of developmental disabilities and the presumed limits to inclusive education.', '2009-05-08 05:37:41', '', 'Inclusive post-secondary education for students with significant developmental disabilities: challenging legal, moral and pragmatic assumptions', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2007', '2', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'Uditsky and Hughson.Inclusive post-secondary education', 'National-Louis University', 'http://www.nl.edu/dse/docs/Uditsky%20and%20Hughson.Inclusive%20post-secondary%20education.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '18', 0, 0, '', '', 'Uditsky, B., & Hughson, A. (2007). <I>Inclusive post-secondary education for students with significant developmental disabilities: challenging legal, moral and pragmatic assumptions.</I> Retrieved June 18 from National-Louis University Web site: http://www.nl.edu/dse/docs/Uditsky%20and%20Hughson.Inclusive%20post-secondary%20education.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;4;6', '4;7;10'),
(1096, 2, 0, '', 'For Purchase', 0, 1, 1, 'Nurse Practitioners (NPs) are persons who work with children and adolescents with Down Syndrome in primary, specialty and acute health care settings.  NPs must have knowledge of the medical, developmental, educational, and social needs of young people with Down Syndrome, and must also have knowledge about the legal policies affecting persons with disabilities.  This clinical report summarizes current clinical practice guidelines.  Pages 200 to 202 of the article examine educational issues, including transition and postsecondary options. Includes a list of internet and print resources of interest to individuals with Down syndrome.', '2009-05-08 05:59:17', '', 'Part II: Clinical practice guidelines for adolescents and young adults with Down Syndrome: 12 to 21 years', 1021, 'Journal of Pediatric Health Care', '0891-5245', '20', '3', '', '', '', '2006', '1', 0, 0, 0, 198, 205, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Van Cleve, S. N., Canon, S., & Cohen, W. (2006). Part II: Clinical practice guidelines for adolescents and young adults with Down Syndrome: 12 to 21 years. <I>Journal of Pediatric Health Care, 20(3), </I> 198-205.', '', '', '', '', '', '3', '4;5;7'),
(1097, 1, 0, '1', 'ISBN: 1557667136', 0, 1, 0, 'This book is a call to action and an in-depth look at promoting inclusive, fulfilling daytimes for adults with intellectual and developmental disabilities. Relevant chapters include â€œPreparing for Meaningful Adult Lives Through School and Transition Experiencesâ€ (Rogan,P. Luecking, R. & Grossi, T.), and â€œCreating Inclusive Post Secondary Educational Environmentsâ€ (Smith, V. & Walker, P.).', '2009-05-08 06:06:48', 'Make the day matter. Promoting typical lifestyles for adults with significant disabilities', '', 0, '', '1557667136', '', '', '', '', '', '2007', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN: 1557667136', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Walker, P. M., & Rogan, P. (2007). <I>Make the day matter. Promoting typical lifestyles for adults with significant disabilities</I>. Baltimore, MD: Paul H. Brookes.', '', 'Paul H. Brookes', 'Baltimore', 'MD', '1;2;3;6', '4;5;7'),
(1098, 1, 0, '', 'ISBN-1-55766-528-1', 0, 1, 0, 'This book is intended as a text or resource for preservice or inservice training of general and special education teachers, and has an orientation for the education of the mentally retarded that is values-based, issues-oriented, and practice-oriented. The 17 chapters are organized into four sections. The first two chapters are introductory and define key concepts such as "mental retardation,""curriculum design," and "curriculum decision making." Chapter 3 considers what is meant by "access to the general curriculum," and describes a framework of curricular modifications that provides access as well as a decision-making model. Subsequent chapters expand on the Individualized Education Program team''s role by discussing person-centered, student-directed planning and student program evaluation based on themes of empowerment. Chapters 7 through 9 describe how to create a learning community, what classroom-level curriculum and instructional decisions can affect progress, and what teaching strategies work to enable students to progress in the general curriculum. Chapters 10 through 16 focus on specific issues including: achieving effective home-school partnerships; classroom management through positive behavioral supports; promoting self-determination; functional academics; community-based instruction; sexuality and social inclusion; and assistive technology. The final chapter provides a summary of the processes presented.', '2009-05-08 06:14:06', 'Teaching students with mental retardation: Providing access to the general curriculum', '', 0, '', '1-55766-528-1', '', '', '', '', '', '2002', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN-1-55766-528-1', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Wehmeyer, M. L., Sands, D. J., Knowlton, E., & Kozleski, E. B. (2002). <I>Teaching students with mental retardation: Providing access to the general curriculum.</I> Baltimore, MD: Brookes Publishing.', '', 'Brookes Publishing', 'Baltimore', 'MD', '2;6', '4;5;9;12'),
(1099, 8, 0, '', 'Originally published as a journal article in a publication called Crossing Boundaries.', 0, 0, 1, 'This paper reports the results of study undertaken to describe a new adult education phenomenon called Inclusive Post-Secondary Education (IPSE). From\r\ninterviews with senior staff members of three IPSE programs in Alberta, Canada, an operational definition of common practices across IPSE programs was developed.\r\nInterviews also produced a listing of benefits and outcomes for students attending these\r\nprograms. Results of this study indicate a common operational model that could be\r\nreplicated elsewhere; as well as describing some philosophical premises that appear to\r\nbe inherent in the operation of IPSE programs.', '2009-05-08 06:18:19', '', 'College and university? You''ve got to be kidding: Inclusive post-secondary education for adults with developmental disabilities', 0, '', 'Unknown', '1', '2', '', '', '', '2002', '', 0, 0, 0, 28, 37, 0, 'College_and_University_You_ve_Got_to_be_Kidding', 'Steps Forward', 'http://www.steps-forward.org/College_and_University_You_ve_Got_to_be_Kidding.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '18', 0, 0, '', '', 'Weinkauf, T. (2002). <I>College and university? You''ve got to be kidding: Inclusive post-secondary education for adults with developmental disabilities. Crossing Boundaries, 1(2), 28-37</I>Retrieved February 18, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://www.steps-forward.org/College_and_University_You_ve_Got_to_be_Kidding.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4', '4;5;7'),
(1100, 8, 0, '', 'Masters Thesis', 0, 0, 1, 'This study explores and describes the practice of including adults with intellectual disabilities into mainstream post-secondary education. Through purposive interviews with senior staff members of Inclusive Post-Secondary Education programs, the data reveals an emerging education experience for adults with intellectual disabilities that benefits more than just these exceptional students. This adult education initiative has the potential to redefine what post-secondary education is about, as well as what might be possible for graduates of special education public schooling. The results of this study are described through journal articles and a conference proceeding.', '2009-05-08 06:28:07', '', 'Inclusive post-secondary education: Practices for a new frontier', 0, '', '9780612604025', '', '', '', '', '', '2001', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Inclusive_Post-Secondary_Education_Practices_for_a_new_frontier', 'Steps Forward', 'http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Inclusive_Post-Secondary_Education_Practices_for_a_new_frontier.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '20', 0, 0, '', '', 'Weinkauf, T. (2001). <I>Inclusive post-secondary education: Practices for a new frontier.</I>Retrieved February 20, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Inclusive_Post-Secondary_Education_Practices_for_a_new_frontier.pdf', '', '', '', '1;3;4', '2;4;5;7;9;10'),
(1101, 13, 0, '', 'On Campus Outreach Fact Sheet #7.  College Park: University of Maryland.', 0, 0, 1, 'This fact sheet is designed to assist students with significant disabilities who may wish to continue their education by attending college during their last years of public school or once they have completed public school. It shares success stories of students and the lessons that have been learned through these and other experiences.', '2009-05-08 06:34:16', '', 'Individual supports for college success', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2001', '1', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Weir factsheet7', 'University of Maryland', 'http://www.education.umd.edu/oco/training/pubs/factsheets/factsheet7.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'Weir, C. (2001). <I>Individual supports for college success.  College Park, MD: On Campus Outreach, University of Maryland.</I> Retrieved February 12, 2009, from University of Maryland Web site: http://www.education.umd.edu/oco/training/pubs/factsheets/factsheet7.pdf', '', '', '', '5;6', '5;6;9'),
(1102, 9, 0, '', 'Part of TASH Connections Collection on ERIC.\r\nURL: links to whole issue.', 0, 0, 1, 'This â€œcall to actionâ€ encourages the reader to challenge the prejudiced assumptions that underlie the exclusion of persons with disabilities from higher education, and bring full inclusion to postsecondary settings. The article explains that the notion of disability is a social construct, and that exclusion on the basis of disability is in fact oppression. The authors situate the exclusion of persons with disabilities from higher education within an understanding that historically, colleges have maintained exclusive environments by restricting access among marginalized groups. The authors also deconstruct the desire to protect persons with intellectual disabilities from failure as a form of paternalism that upholds oppression. College success stories of persons with intellectual disabilities are included, highlighting the importance of genuinely supporting individualsâ€™ high expectations, dreams and goals.', '2009-05-08 06:45:13', 'Tash Connection', 'Inclusion goes to college: A call to action', 0, '', '', '27', '2', '', '', '', '2001', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Tash Connections Weir etc', 'ERIC', 'http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/1a/29/4e.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '19', 0, 0, '', '', 'Weir, C., Tashie, C., & Rossetti, Z. (2001). Inclusion goes to college: A call to action. <I>Tash Conenctions 27(2)</I> Retrieved February 19, 2009, from ERIC database: http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICDocs/data/ericdocs2sql/content_storage_01/0000019b/80/1a/29/4e.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '4;5;6;10;12'),
(1103, 14, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'The article is meant to be a first step for individuals with autism spectrum disorders and parents interested in post-secondary options. This article highlights questions that are important to address when beginning the exploration process of post-secondary education.', '2009-05-08 07:47:21', '', 'The road to post-secondary education: Questions to consider', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2000', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 'Access Autism', 'http://www.iidc.indiana.edu/irca/education/questions.html', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '20', 0, 0, '', '', 'Wheeler, M., & Kalina, N., (2000). <I>The road to post-secondary education: Questions to consider.</I> Retrieved February 20, 2009, from Indiana University Web site: http://www.iidc.indiana.edu/irca/education/questions.html', '', '', '', '5;6', '4;5;6;7;9'),
(1104, 9, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'This article explores the role of postsecondary education in Maricel Donezaâ€™s transition to adulthood, situating her experience within an ecological model that explores the interaction of her postsecondary experience with her identity in family, cultural and community life. A student with intellectual disabilities, Maricel Doneza broke through barriers of discrimination, and completed a certificate in early childhood education, enabling her employment as a teacherâ€™s assistant in a preschool â€“ the occupation of her choice.  Her academic and career successes parallel successful transitions in her personal life, including obtaining a drivers license, cooking meals, grocery shopping, and budgeting money.  The authorâ€™s account of Maricel Doenzaâ€™s experience highlights the transformative power of personal self-determination and of family, cultural and community support when pursuing ones dreams.', '2009-05-08 08:10:43', 'Tash Connections', 'Maricel becomes her own person within her family, culture, and community', 0, '', '', '31', '11/12', '', '', '', '2005', '', 0, 0, 0, 18, 20, 0, 'TASH Connections Nov Dec 2005', '', 'http://wwwdev.hawaii.edu/surge/uploads/5/4fa1342cbd3e3aba10f90f3f52d574e7.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '10', '10', 0, 0, '', '', 'Whelley, T. (2005). <I>Maricel becomes her own person within her family, culture, and community. </I>Tash Connections 31(11/12). Retrieved October 10, 2009, from University of Hawaii Website: http://wwwdev.hawaii.edu/surge/uploads/5/4fa1342cbd3e3aba10f90f3f52d574e7.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '4;5;7;9;11;12'),
(1105, 13, 12, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'This paper examines the often overwhelming and confusing process associated with finding and accessing services and supports encountered by students\r\nwith disabilities in secondary schools as they prepare to attend postsecondary education and/or engage in employment The white paper presents: (1) A description of problems related to coordination and management of services and supports, and the subsequent impact on outcomes for youth with disabilities as they exit secondary schools. Four major barriers related to coordination and management of services identified in the literature are discussed; (2) A conceptual model, which addresses the four key barriers, is developed; (3) Current practice in the area of coordination and management of services and supports is discussed; (4) Emerging promising practices that begin to address the four barriers are described; (5) Recommendations for further research and practice as they relate to the four major barriers to effective coordination and management of services are offered.', '2009-05-08 08:55:33', 'White Paper', 'Coordination and management of services and supports for individuals with disabilities from secondary to postsecondary education and employment', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2004', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Whelley Hart Zafft 04', 'The Rehabilitation Research and Training Center, University of Hawaii at Manoa', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase3/04.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'Whelley, T., Hart, D., & Zafft, C. (2004). <I>Coordination and management of services and supports for individuals with disabilities from secondary to postsecondary education and employment. Retrieved February 12, 2009, from University of Hawaii Web site: http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase3/04.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;6', '2;4;5;6;7;9;10;12'),
(1106, 14, 0, '', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Educational Supports, University of Hawaii Manoa', 0, 0, 1, 'Students Speak: Stories of Postsecondary Education represent a collection of selfâ€reports by students with intellectual disabilities who are either planning to attend postsecondary education, are currently attending postsecondary education, or have attended postsecondary education. The intent of this booklet is to illustrate successful strategies for inclusion in postsecondary education in the studentâ€™s voices and to reveal the possible richness of typical life for students with intellectual disabilities given commitment to inclusive education communities. No analysis or comments are offered by others so as to allow the studentsâ€™ experiences, relationships, hopes, and goals reveal themselves.', '2009-05-08 09:11:01', '', 'Students speak: Stories of postsecondary education.', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2003', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'wholestory', 'Think College', 'http://www.thinkcollege.net/pdfs/wholestory.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '22', 0, 0, '', '', 'Whelley. T., & Yaganeh, M., (2003). <I>Students speak: Stories of postsecondary education. Honolulu, HI: National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Educational Supports, University of Hawaii Manoa.</I> Retrieved February 22, 2009, from Think College Web site: http://www.thinkcollege.net/pdfs/wholestory.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '4;5;6;12'),
(1107, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'Increasing numbers of students with disabilities are pursuing post-secondary education. Many campuses are not yet equipped to meet the unique and diverse needs of students with disabilities. This article examines programs, services and programs aimed at promoting studentsâ€™ choice, independence, social participation, and supports needed for academic success.  Virginia Commonwealth University (VCU) has developed and implemented a comprehensive disability services program using a decentralized disability services model. The goal of decentralization is to create a more welcoming and supportive campus climate. Training and professional development is a significant component of the program. This article describes the initial stage of the programâ€™s development and implementation, within which a comprehensive formative evaluation of services and supports was embedded.', '2009-05-08 09:17:28', '', 'Enhancing the post-secondary campus climate for students with disabilities', 1026, 'Journal of Vocational Rehabilitation', '1052-2263', '14', '1', '', '', '', '2000', '', 0, 0, 0, 37, 50, 0, 'Enhancing_the_post_secondary_campus_climate_for_students_with_disabilities', 'Steps Forward', 'http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Enhancing_the_post_secondary_campus_climate_for_students_with_disabilities.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '12', 0, 0, 'Wilson, K., Getzel, E., & Brown, T. (2000). Enhancing the post-secondary campus climate for students with disabilities. <I>Journal of Vocational Rehabilitation, 14(1), </I> 37-50.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '4;5;6;7;9'),
(1108, 2, 9, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'Abstract: This paper presents a qualitative study of the experiences of three transition-aged students with intellectual disabilities, their parent(s), faculty, and Disability Services Office (DSO) professionals after the students had taken at least two courses at their local community college. The students were part of the College Career Connection (CCC) project, a cohort of 25 high school students in Massachusetts, age 18-22, who were supported in inclusive postsecondary education by their high school and the Institute for Community Inclusion (ICI) at the University of Massachusetts - Boston. The focus is on understanding academic accommodation using a semi-structured interview format of core questions and additional questions created for each specific role (student, parent, faculty, etc.). Extensive quotes from the interviews are used to illustrate key themes.', '2009-05-08 09:25:00', '', 'A case study of accommodations for transition - age students with intellectual disabilities', 1022, 'Journal of Postsecondary Education and Disability', 'NA', '18', '2', '', '', '', '2006', '1', 0, 0, 0, 167, 175, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Zafft, C. (2006). A case study of accommodations for transition - age students with intellectual disabilities. <I>Journal of Postsecondary Education and Disability, 18(2), 167-175.</I> -.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '4;5;6;7;9;12');
