(1036, 2, 0, '', 'http://www.lovepublishing.com/catalog/focus_on_exceptional_children_31.html', 0, 1, 1, 'This article presents an overview of options that improve access to age appropriate educational and transition experiences for youth with significant disabilities ages 18-21. The article describes two models for providing access to post secondary education: (a) programs that serve public school students in college and community settings, and (b) individual support approaches for serving public school students in college and community settings. For each model, the authors highlight the key features and settings, opportunities for inclusion, funding, logistics, and interagency linkages, and identify replication and evaluation needs', '2009-04-30 08:40:30', '', 'Postsecondary education and transition services for students ages 18-21 with significant disabilities', 1013, 'Focus on Exceptional Children', '0015-511X', '34', '8', '', '', '', '2002', '2', 0, 0, 0, 1, 12, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Neubert, D. A., Moon, M, S., & Grigal, M. (2002). Postsecondary education and transition services for students ages 18-21 with significant disabilities. <I>Focus on Exceptional Children, 34(8), </I> 1-12.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;4;6', '1;3;4;5;9'),
(1037, 2, 0, '', 'http://www.iospress.nl/loadtop/load.php?isbn=10522263', 0, 1, 1, 'Providing opportunities for individuals with mental retardation and other significant disabilities to participate in educational, vocational, and recreational activities on college campuses has been a topic of interest among educators and adult service providers for the past 30 years. We reviewed the literature on post-secondary programs and supports for these individuals to (a) identify a philosophical basis for providing such opportunities, (b) identify practices, and (c) summarize research on the efficacy of these efforts. The literature from the 1970''s to 1990''s provided descriptions of programs or advocated for the inclusion of adults with mental retardation on college campuses in position papers. Limited empirical data supported the efficacy of these programs. The literature during the 1990''s shifted to providing post-secondary programs or individual supports to students with mental retardation and other significant disabilities, ages 18--22, who were still enrolled in public schools. Implications for emerging trends, research and program evaluation, and replication of practices are discussed.', '2009-04-30 09:02:34', '', 'Postsecondary educational practices for individuals with mental retardation and other significant disabilities', 1026, 'Journal of Vocational Rehabilitation', '1052-2263', '16', '3-4', '', '', '', '2001', '', 0, 0, 0, 155, 168, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Neubert, D. A., Moon, M. S., Grigal, M., & Redd, V. A. (2001). Postsecondary educational practices for individuals with mental retardation and other significant disabilities. <I>Journal of Vocational Rehabilitation, 16(3-4), </I> 155-168.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;6', '2;5;9;11'),
(1038, 2, 0, '', 'http://www.dddcec.org/publications.htm#ETDD', 1, 1, 1, 'In 1995, the Southwest Special Education Local Plan Area (SELPA) of the Los Angeles County School District, and El Camino College pioneered a partnership to serve students with disabilities on the community college campus. SELPA transition services serve as a model for alliances between community colleges and school districts throughout California. Area students receiving special education services have an opportunity to pursue postsecondary education while completing high school requirements. Students attend college classes, participate in social activities, and learn life and employment skills. Students learn to be successful at achieving goals through SELPA partnerships. The school district and community college alliance, activities, and services are described, using program theory as the means of identifying the flow and sequence of the program. (Contains 1 figure.)', '2009-04-30 09:16:54', '', 'Transition services model: Partnership for student success', 1008, 'Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities', '1547-0350', '39', '1', '', '', '', '2004', '1', 0, 0, 0, 26, 34, 0, 'Pearman, Elliott, Aborn 2004', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Pearman, E., Elliott, T., & Aborn, L. (2004). Transition services model: Partnership for student success. <I>Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities, 39(1), </I> 26-34.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '1;4;5;11'),
(1039, 8, 8, '', '', 0, 1, 1, '	Since the early 1990''s there is a growing interest in providing inclusive age-appropriate experiences to students who are ages 18 to 21, with significant disabilities, and are still enrolled in public schools. These efforts have resulted in local school systems (LSS) developing programs and services that are located in the community and on college campuses. Although there is a body of literature on postsecondary opportunities for these students, little is known about the programs and supports provided, or the views of consumers. In an effort to extend the literature, a case-study approach was used to gather information on a program located in a community college. Observations, individual interviews, focus groups, and document reviews were used to address the following: (a) What criteria (i.e., rationale for development, allocation of resources, staffing decisions, admission into program, factors that facilitate or act as barriers to program development and sustainability) are employed in the development and implementation of a public school-sponsored program for students ages 18 to 21 with SD within a community college campus?; (b) What program components described in the literature as best practices for secondary students with significant disabilities are incorporated in this public school-sponsored program located on a community college campus?; and Â© What are the students'' and parents'' views on the role of this public school-sponsored postsecondary program for students with SD ages 18 to 21 in preparing students for the future? Software designed for use in qualitative research was used to sort and code information, and data were triangulated across methods, informants, and analysts. Findings suggest that although the LSS developed and operated the program on a community college campus, students received segregated instruction (e.g., functional academics, social skills, independent living skills) and students had limited interactions with typical college students and limited opportunities for self-determination. However, students and parents were satisfied with the program, and students who exited the program experienced no disruption in services during the transition into the adult services system. Implications for future practice and research, and limitations of the study are discussed.', '2009-04-30 09:31:09', '', 'A public school-sponsored program for students ages 18 to 21 with significant disabilities located on a community college campus: A case study', 0, '', 'http://hdl.handle.net/1903/1727', '', '', '', '', '', '2004', '1', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Redd 2004', '', 'http://www.lib.umd.edu/drum/bitstream/1903/1727/1/umi-umd-1698.pdf', 'http://hdl.handle.net/1903/1727', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '15', 0, 0, '', '', 'Redd, V. A. (2004). A public school-sponsored program for students ages 18 to 21 with significant disabilities located on a community college campus: A case study. (Doctoral dissertation, University of Maryland, 2004). Retrieved February 15, 2009, from University of Maryland Web Site: ttp://www.lib.umd.edu/drum/bitstream/1903/1727/1/umi-umd-1698.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '1;2;4;5;11;12'),
(1040, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'An inclusive, zero-reject adult education program supported students with mild to severe developmental disabilities in their participation in mainstream education in Finland in various institutions, such as vocational schools, institutes, and university faculties. While not formally enrolled as students of these institutions, they were allowed to participate. Their curricula were individually adapted, and they received support from program facilitators and student volunteers. Experiences of the first 15 students in the program indicated that students themselves, their families, and the program facilitators, although evaluations differed with settings, evaluated the program and its results positively.', '2009-04-30 09:41:47', '', 'An inclusive adult education program for students with mild to severe developmental disabilities: Experiences from a pilot project in Finland', 1006, 'Developmental Disabilities Bulletin', '1184-0412', '28', '', '', '', '', '2000', '', 0, 0, 0, 27, 39, 0, 'Saloviita 2000', 'Steps Forward', 'http://steps-forward.org/Research-Finland.html', '', '', '', '', '2009', '3', '7', 0, 0, 'Saloviita, T. (2000). An inclusive adult education program for students with mild to severe developmental disabilities: Experiences from a pilot project in Finland. <I>Developmental Disabilities Bulletin, 28, </I> 27-39.', '', 'Saloviita, T. (2000). <I>An inclusive adult education program for students with mild to severe developmental disabilities: Experiences from a pilot project in Finland.</I> Retrieved March 7, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://steps-forward.org/Research-Finland.html', '', '', '', '1;6', '2;5'),
(1041, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'Legislation in recent years, including the ADA , IDEA, and the Olmstead Act, has vastly affected the accessibility of postsecondary education for persons with disabilities. This paper presents an overview of that legislation and considers how the resultant supports and services have become more flexible and increasingly tailored to the individual''s unique educational needs and academic/professional goals. This paper also examines a sampling of educational models and projects that have been undertaken with the intent of maximizing accessibility and inclusion, and it looks at the various issues concerning supports, policy, financial concerns, and systemic coordination that arise from those models and projects. Finally, the need for future research is addressed, and questions intended to give direction thereto are posed.', '2009-04-30 09:50:28', '', 'Postsecondary education and persons with intellectual disabilities: An introduction', 1008, 'Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities', '1547-0350', '39', '1', '', '', '', '2004', '1', 0, 0, 0, 6, 15, 0, 'Stodden, Whelley 2004', '', 'http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Research.html', '', '', '', '', '2009', '3', '21', 0, 0, 'Stodden, R. A., & Whelley, T. (2004). Postsecondary education and persons with intellectual disabilities: An introduction. <I>Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities, 39(1), </I> 6-15.', '', 'Stodden, R. A., & Whelley, T. (2004). <I>Postsecondary education and persons with intellectual disabilities: An introduction. Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities, </I> Retrieved March 21, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Research.html', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '1;2;3;4;5;7;9;11'),
(1042, 2, 0, '', 'Available with Springer Link access or article purchase', 0, 1, 1, 'In the 1990â€™s a surge of children were diagnosed with autism spectrum disorders (ASDs) and are now approaching college age. Through early diagnosis and intervention many of these children are now able to consider post secondary education. However, these students will need specific interventions and supports in order to be successful. This article reviews the nosology of ASDs, the legal basis for providing accommodations to students on the autism spectrum, and the incidence and prevalence of ASDs. The authors provide specific recommendations regarding the academic, independent living, social, vocational and counseling needs of college students who are on the autism spectrum. With a carefully planned transition, appropriate accommodations, and support, ASD students can be successful academically and socially in college.', '2009-04-30 10:01:59', '', 'Supporting more able students on the autism spectrum: College and beyond', 1019, 'Journal of Autism and Developmental Disorders', 'print: 0162-3257 electronic: 1573-3432', '38', '7', '', '', '', '2008', '4', 0, 0, 0, 1359, 1370, 0, '', 'Spring Link', 'http://www.springerlink.com/content/x711353873813ung/', '10.1007/s10803-007-0524-8', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Van Bergeijk, E. K., & Ami Volkmar, F. (2008). Supporting more able students on the autism spectrum: College and beyond. <I>Journal of Autism and Developmental Disorders, 38(7), </I> 1359-1370.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '6;7;9;11'),
(1043, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'Recent studies of innovative supports and services in postsecondary education reveal more effective and cooperative mechanisms with which to provide supports to individuals with disabilities (Stodden, Jones, & Chang, 2003; Whelley, Hart, & Zafft, 2003). Colleges and universities can design supports that permit consumer choice while avoiding establishment of isolating parallel "service systems." Providing individual supports for students with significant disabilities will establish new and creative alliances driven by wishes and dreams of the students. This paper is a participant observation, discussing individual and collaborative supports, providing a discussion of and recommendations for effective strategies, and presenting successful students who have pursued their dreams of postsecondary education.', '2009-04-30 10:29:15', '', 'Person-centered and collaborative supports for college success', 1008, 'Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities', '1547-0350', '39', '1', '', '', '', '2004', '1', 0, 0, 0, 67, 73, 0, 'etdd article weir-1', 'Transition to College', 'http://www.transitiontocollege.net/percpubs/etdd%20article%20weir-1.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '22', 0, 0, 'Weir, C. (2004). Person-centered and collaborative supports for college success. <I>Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities, 39(1), </I> 67-73.', '', 'Weir, C. (2004). <I>Person-centered and collaborative supports for college success.</I> Retrieved February 22, 2009, from Transition to College Web site: http://www.transitiontocollege.net/percpubs/etdd%20article%20weir-1.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '4;5;7;9;11;12'),
(1044, 2, 0, '', 'Ordering info: \r\nhttp://www.dddcec.org/publications.htm#ETDD', 0, 1, 1, 'Participation in postsecondary education is a known predictor of a successful employment outcome for youth without disabilities. There is research documenting that this is true for youth with disabilities as well. Most literature on postsecondary education for youth with disabilities focuses on individuals with learning disabilities, attention deficit disorders, and physical or sensory disorders. There is limited research that addresses youth with intellectual disabilities regarding successful outcomes of participation in postsecondary education. This paper presents findings from a matched cohort follow-up study conducted with 40 youth with significant disabilities who did and did not participate in postsecondary education. Recommendations for future research and practice are provided.', '2009-04-30 10:49:51', '', 'College career connection: A study of youth with intellectual disabilities and the impact of postsecondary education', 1008, 'Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities', '1547-0350', '39', '1', '', '', '', '2004', '1', 0, 0, 0, 45, 54, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Zafft, C., Hart, D., & Zimbrich, K. (2004). College career connection: A study of youth with intellectual disabilities and the impact of postsecondary education. <I>Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities, 39(1), </I> 45-54.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;6', '1;2;4;5;7;9;11;12'),
(1049, 1, 0, '1', 'ED491343\r\nISBN-0-8907-9993-8\r\npages.', 0, 1, 0, 'This publication provides a framework and strategies to (a) develop transition services for youth with significant disabilities in college and community settings, (b) evaluate the success of such programs, and (c) expand successful transition programs.  Chapter 1 provides a comprehensive overview of the steps needed to initiate new programs, including how to create a planning committee, and how to conduct a needs assessment for both students services and for community partnerships.  Chapter 2 describes the policy and procedural aspects of transition service delivery in college and community settings. Staffing, referral, transportation, and budget issues are discussed. The chapter also presents strategies for ensuring that studentsâ€™ experiences are authentically inclusive, and discusses how to schedule student supports and monitor student and staff activities. Chapter 3 presents and overview of evaluation methods  appropriate to assess the merit of transition services in college and community settings. This book includes profiles of successful programs, examples of completed forms, and numerous blank forms which may copied and used for the planning, implementation, and evaluation of transition programs in college and community settings.  The book is accompanied by a CD Rom that allows readers to adapt forms to meet each programâ€™s unique needs.', '2009-04-30 11:48:13', 'Transition services for students with SD in college and community settings: Strategies for planning, implementation, and evaluation', '', 0, '', '0-89079-993-8', '', '', '', '', '', '2005', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN-0-8907-9993-8', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Grigal, M., Neubert, D. A., & Moon, M. S. (2005). <I>Transition services for students with SD in college and community settings: Strategies for planning, implementation, and evaluation</I>. Austin, TX: PRO-ED.', '', 'PRO-ED', 'Austin', 'TX', '1;2;3;4;6', '2;4;5;7;9;11'),
(1050, 4, 9, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'This report seeks to provide a comprehensive overview and critical analysis of inclusive post-secondary education across all Alberta initiatives. As a result of twenty years of experience supporting the inclusion of individuals with developmental disabilities in colleges and universities, a substantial number of students, peers, faculty, facilitators, families and employers can describe and explain the value of inclusive post-secondary education. This study collected information about studentsâ€™ employment, living arrangements, social life and other contributions to the community.  The study examined the impact of attending colleges and universities, as well the critical factors influencing the experiences of students, families, faculty and employers in Canadian communities. This qualitative study used a participatory action research design, and research findings address employment as well as social emotional and affective outcomes of postsecondary educational experiences.', '2009-04-30 12:02:08', '', 'The story of inclusive post secondary education in Alberta, final research report 2004-2005', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2006', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'The_Story_of_Inclusive_Post_Secondary_Education_in_Alberta.pdf', 'Steps Forward Inclusive Post Secondary Education Society', 'http://www.steps-forward.org/The_Story_of_Inclusive_Post_Secondary_Education_in_Alberta.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '1', 1, 0, '', '', 'Hughson, E. A., Moodie, S., & Uditsky, B. (2006). <I>The story of inclusive post secondary education in Alberta, final research report 2004-2005.</I> Retrieved February 1, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://www.steps-forward.org/The_Story_of_Inclusive_Post_Secondary_Education_in_Alberta.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;4;5;6', '2;5;7;11'),
(1051, 1, 0, '3', 'http://www.amazon.com/Preparing-Life-Transitioning-Adulthood-Aspergers/dp/1932565337', 0, 1, 0, 'This reader-friendly chapter introduces concepts, strategies, tools and resources to help parents ensure their son or daughter enjoys a meaningful life after high school.  The author recommends preparing for transition during the youthâ€™s first year of high school, using a planning approach such as Person Centered Planning. The chapter presents an overview of youthâ€™s rights under section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act, defines accommodations, and provides examples of accommodations currently used in college settings.  Included are descriptions of resources for income supports (e.g. SSI, SSDI) employment services (e.g. Vocational Rehabilitation, One Stop Career Centers), and residential services.  The chapter closes with a case study to illustrate the transition planning process. Although some of the information is relevant only to students who enter college through regular admissions processes, the chapter will be useful for individuals and families who seek an easy to read orientation to transition resources and processes.', '2009-04-30 16:08:31', 'Preparing for life: The complete guide for transitioning to adulthood for those with autism and asperger''s syndrome', 'College, career, and residential options beyond high school: What parents can do to prepare their son or daughter.', 0, '', '1932565337', '', '', '', '', '', '2006', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN-10: 1932565337', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Blumberg, R. (2006). College, career, and residential options beyond high school: What parents can do to prepare their son or daughter. In J. Baker (Ed.) <I>Preparing for Life: The Complete Guide for Transitioning to Adulthood for Those with Autism and Asperger''s Syndrome.</I> Arlington, TX: Future Horizons.', '', 'Future Horizons', 'Arlington', 'TX', '2;6', '3;4;7;11'),
(1054, 2, 11, '', 'Incomplete entry published in Entourageâ€¦publishing information unavailable.', 0, 0, 0, 'This article introduces the reader to On Campus, a university based program for students with significant disabilities at the University of Alberta, Canada. Written just a few years after the On Campus program was initiated, the article provides insight into the programâ€™ first goals, structure, and theory of change. Program goals include providing normative and enriching experiences, and developing individualsâ€™ talents, strengths, and interests.  The program theorizes  that meeting these program goals will increase studentsâ€™ self esteem, self efficacy, and opportunities to secure employment after graduation.', '2009-04-30 23:37:25', '', 'On Campus: Integration at university', 0, '', '', '3', '3', '', '', '', '1988', '', 0, 0, 0, 33, 40, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Frank, S. & Uditsky, B. (1988). On Campus: Integration at university. Entourage, 3(3), 33-40.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;4;6', '2;5;9;11;12'),
(1056, 1, 0, '4', 'ISBN-10: 155766917', 0, 1, 0, 'As an increasing number of students with intellectual disabilities are aspiring to attend college, high schools, colleges, and universities must prepare to meet the needs of students with disabilities.  This comprehensive resource presents an overview of post secondary options, and provides guidance on how to support students with disabilities before, during, and after the transition to college. The text includes vignettes and personal narratives by students and their families, and profiles programs currently serving students with intellectual disabilities. Resources provided in the text include a self-advocacy checklist, a program evaluation instrument, sample student schedules, and a college planning checklist for students and families.', '2009-05-01 00:15:49', 'Think college: Postsecondary education options for students with intellectual disabilities', '', 0, '', 'In Press', '', '', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN-10: 155766917', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Grigal, M., & Hart, D. (2009). <I>Think college: Postsecondary education options for students with intellectual disabilities</I>. Baltimore, MD: Brookes Publishing.', '', 'Brookes Publishing', 'Baltimore', 'MD', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '1;2;3;4;5;7;9;11;12'),
(1057, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'This academic paper examines the goals of inclusive postsecondary education for students with intellectual disabilities, within the context of a broader political movement, that of inclusive community living, and explores the limitations of a â€œrightsâ€ discourse as the foundation for advocacy and social change. The author deconstructs the â€œotheringâ€ of persons with disabilities, exposes the separate special education system as a form of institutional exclusion and oppression, and asserts that full inclusion is possible through modifications and adaptations to curriculum and instruction. However, in order for these institutional changes to occur, educators must re-envision inclusion, rather than exclusion, as the normative practice of educational institutions.  The article includes profiles of inclusive postsecondary educational programs in Canada and examines the current state of research supporting full inclusion in postsecondary settings.', '2009-05-01 00:21:56', '', 'Inclusive post-secondary education: Human rights can legislate change but can it(sic) create acceptance?', 0, '', 'Appendix A', '', '', '', '', '', '2003', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'Inclusive_Post-Secondary_Education_Human_Rights_can_Legislate_Change', 'Steps Forward Inclusive Post Secondary Education Society', 'http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Inclusive_Post-Secondary_Education_Human_Rights_can_Legislate_Change.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '3', '18', 0, 0, '', '', 'Guenette, F. (2003). <I>Inclusive post-secondary education: Human rights can legislate change but can it(sic) create acceptance?</I> Retrieved March 18, 2009 from Steps Forward Web site: http://stepsforward.homestead.com/Inclusive_Post-Secondary_Education_Human_Rights_can_Legislate_Change.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '4;5;7;8;9;12'),
(1058, 13, 4, '', 'Issue Brief Examining Current Challenges in Secondary Education and Transition', 0, 1, 1, 'This paper addresses the question of how interagency service coordination for youth with disabilities can be more flexible, youth centered, and culturally responsive.  Poor interagency service coordination creates barriers to postsecondary educational access.  These barriers are even more prominent for students with significant disabilities. The authors identify four models of service coordination represented in the literature and four major barriers to effective service coordination and management of supports. Recommendations for resolving major barriers are presented.', '2009-05-01 07:10:16', 'Issue Brief Examining Current Challenges in Secondary Education and Transition', 'Challenges in coordinating and managing services and supports in secondary and postsecondary options', 0, '', '', '1', '6', '', '', '', '2002', '7', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'NCSETIssueBrief_1.6', 'NCSET', 'http://www.ncset.org/publications/viewdesc.asp?id=719', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'Hart, D., Zimbrich, K., & Whelley, T. (2002). <I>Challenges in coordinating and managing services and supports in secondary and postsecondary options.</I> Retrieved June 12, 2009, from NCSET Web site: http://www.ncset.org/publications/viewdesc.asp?id=719', '', '', '', '1;2;3', '4;5;7;9;11'),
(1059, 13, 0, '', 'Available online to TASH members only.', 0, 1, 1, 'A speech professor from Kapiolani Community College and his former student Cassilly Woll, who is a  student with an intellectual disabilty, discuss their experiences teaching and learning through Cassillyâ€™s participation in community college. This article discusses Cassillyâ€™s contributions to the class content and climate as well as her use of accommodations such as a notetaker. Encouragement and support from family and friends factored prominently in her account.  The article is written in an interview format, giving voice to both teacher and student. A video about Cassilly Wollâ€™s success in college entitled â€œCassilly: How I Went to Collegeâ€ produced by the Center on Disability Studies at the University of Hawaii Manoa is referenced. The video is currently being used to help secondary and postsecondary teachers embrace college as a transition option for persons with intellectual disabilities.', '2009-05-01 07:25:17', 'Tash Connections', 'Teaching and learning in a community college: Reflections of a teacher and a student', 0, '', '', '31', '11/12', '', '', '', '2005', '', 0, 0, 0, 24, 26, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Johnson, B., & Woll, C. (2005). Teaching and learning in a community college: Reflections of a teacher and a student. <I>, Tash Connections, 31(11/12), </I> 24-26.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '5;7;9;12'),
(1060, 2, 0, '', 'Available to CEC members\r\nEJ650434', 0, 1, 1, 'The transition challenges discussed are to ensure that (1) students have access to the full range of curriculum options and learning experiences; (2) high school graduation decisions are based on meaningful indicators of learning; (3) students have access to postsecondary education, employment, and independent living options; (4) student and family participation are supported; and (5) interagency collaboration is improved.', '2009-05-01 07:41:11', '', 'Current challenges facing secondary education and transition services: What research tells us', 1010, 'Exceptional Children', '0014-4029', '68', '4', '', '', '', '2002', '1', 0, 0, 0, 519, 531, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Johnson, D., R., Stodden, R., A., Emanuel, E., J., Luecking, R., & Mack, M. (2002). Current challenges facing secondary education and transition services: What research tells us. <I>Exceptional Children, 68(4), </I>519-531.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4', '4;5;7;11'),
(1061, 13, 4, '', 'PHASE II\r\nPROPOSAL BRIEF #9', 0, 0, 1, 'This proposal brief describes the National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Educational Supports'' research questions and activities for an exploratory pilot study of the extent to which students with intellectual disabilities are included in post secondary education settings.', '2009-05-01 07:58:18', '', 'Examination of the status of inclusion of students with developmental, including significant cognitive, disabilities in post-secondary education settings', 0, '', 'Phase II Proposal Brief #9', '', '', '', '', '', '2001', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'Johnson024a(2)-H01', 'The Rehabilitation Research and Training Center', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase2/pdf/024a(2)-H01.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'Johnson, J. (2001). <I>Examination of the status of inclusion of students with developmental, including significant cognitive, disabilities in post-secondary education settings.</I> Retrieved June 12, 2009, from University of Hawaii Web site: http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase2/pdf/024a%282%29-H01.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;4', '2;5;7'),
(1062, 8, 5, '', 'Coalition for the Support of Individuals with Significant Disabilities in Postsecondary Education', 0, 0, 0, 'A community college professor reflects on his experiences teaching students with disabilities. He describes the learning trajectories of three students with disabilities who participated in his Speech course. The author implies, but does not state directly that one of the students may be an individual with an intellectual disability. Curriculum and assessment modifications for this student included an oral exam that focused on essential information. The author reflects that this studentâ€™s accomplishments challenged his preconceptions regarding who is capable of engaging with college level curriculum. A description of Kapiâ€™olani Community Collegeâ€™s open door policy is included.\r\n\r\nPaper presented at the Second Summit of the Coalition for the Support of Individuals with Significant Disabilities in Postsecondary Education, Boston.', '2009-05-01 08:17:47', '', 'Serving students with disabilities: Reflections of a community college teacher', 0, '', 'presentation', '', '', '', '', '', '2002', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', '', 'Johnson, R. (2002). <I>Serving students with disabilities: Reflections of a community college teacher. Paper presented at the Second Summit of the Coalition for the Support of Individuals with Significant Disabilities in Postsecondary Education,</I> Boston.', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '5;7'),
(1063, 8, 5, '', 'Paper presented @ ISEC 2000Margaret Maciver - Manukau Institute of Technology Auckland, New Zealand', 0, 0, 1, 'This paper discusses the growth and subsequent decline of these tertiary programs and focuses on the issues that have confronted educators and students over the last decade. Legislation afforded this right to education but the subsequent development of policy in New Zealand has systematically excluded this group from post secondary education. As well as outlining the systemic difficulties faced the paper outlines the infrastructure developed by tertiary providers, the development of external support networks and the inclusion of curriculum standards into the NZ National Qualifications Framework.', '2009-05-01 08:22:41', '', 'Who is really moving the margins: The rise and fall of tertiary education for students with and intellectual disability in New Zealand', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2000', '1', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 'ISEC 2000', 'http://www.isec2000.org.uk/abstracts/papers_m/maciver_1.htm', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 1, 0, '', '', 'Maciver, M. (2000). <I>Who is really moving the margins: The rise and fall of tertiary education for students with and intellectual disability in New Zealand.</I> Retrieved June 12, 2009, from ISEC 2000 Web site: http://www.isec2000.org.uk/abstracts/papers_m/maciver_1.htm', '', '', '', '1;2;4;6', '2;5;7;10;11'),
(1064, 8, 5, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'This paper explores how the reauthorization of the Higher Education Act of 1965 may improve access to postsecondary educational institutions for persons with intellectual disabilities. Three categories of the Higher Education Act programs and services are discussed: student financial aid, services to help student complete high school and succeed in postsecondary education, and aid to improve k-12 teacher training at postsecondary institutions.', '2009-05-01 08:30:22', '', 'Opening the door to postsecondary education for all: Public school programs for students with intellectual disabilities in postsecondary settings', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2004', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'Opening The Door Martinez', 'Rehabilitation Research & Training Center', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase3/16.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 1, 0, '', '', 'Martinez, D., C. (2004). <I>Opening the door to postsecondary education for all: Public school programs for students with intellectual disabilities in postsecondary settings.</I> Honolulu, HI: Rehabilitation Research and Training Center at the University of Hawaiâ€™i at Manoa. Retrieved June 12, 2009, from http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase3/16.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '3;5;10'),
(1065, 8, 5, '', 'Archived Resource Paper', 0, 0, 1, 'This paper encourages the reader to envision a future of opportunity and potential for youth with intellectual disabilities. The authors suggest a set of goals to help young adults and their families keep the bar of expectations high. Suggested goals are discussed in depth and include: self determination and self advocacy for successful planning, transition into lifelong learning, self-directed employment success and satisfaction, overcoming the disincentives to work, moving into the neighborhood, financial security, and emerging into adulthood.', '2009-05-01 12:24:35', '', 'Planning for post school outcomes and emerging into adulthood: A resource guide for  parents of youth with intellectual disabilities', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2007', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, '', 'Rehabilitation Research & Training Center', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase3/16.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'Martinez, D. C. (2007). <I>Planning for post school outcomes and emerging into adulthood: A resource guide for  parents of youth with intellectual disabilities.</I>Wahington, DC: The George Washington University Heath Resource Center.  Retrieved June 12, 2009, from http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase3/16.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;5', '4;5;7;11;12'),
(1066, 13, 0, '', 'Fast Facts Publication: Think College!', 0, 0, 1, 'One role of Vocational Rehabilitation is to support postsecondary education in accordance with studentâ€™s Individualized Plans for Employment (IPE). This data note compares the employment outcomes of youth with intellectual disabilities who did and who did not receive postsecondary educational supports as a part of their IPEs.  Data analysis revealed that youth who participated in postsecondary education were 26% more likely to exit the VR program with employment, and their weekly wage earning were 73% higher than those who had no postsecondary education experiences.  This study suggests that postsecondary education for persons with intellectual disabilities is indeed a promising practice.', '2009-05-01 12:50:02', '', 'Postsecondary education and employment outcomes for youth with intellectual disabilities', 0, '', 'Think College! Fast Facts', '1', '', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Fast Facts #1 Think College', 'Think College!', 'http://www.thinkcollege.net/publications', '', '', '', '', '2009', '2', '27', 0, 0, '', '', 'Migliore, A., Butterworth, J., & Hart, D. (2009). Postsecondary education and employment outcomes for youth with intellectual disabilities.<I>Think College! Fast Facts, 1. </I> Retrieved February 27, 2009,  from Think College Web site: http://www.thinkcollege.net/publications', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '4;5;7;11'),
(1067, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'This article provides parents and others the information they may need to initiate postsecondary education options for students with significant disabilities ages 18-21. The article explores the goals programs may wish to address, how students should prepare for such postsecondary education options, as well as the locations, classes and activities that programs typically offer. The article also offers suggestions on how families can garner the institutional and interagency supports needed to staff and sustain new programs.', '2009-05-01 13:10:53', '', 'High school and beyond: Students with significant disabilities complete high school through alternative programs in post-secondary settings', 1011, 'Exceptional Parent', '0046-9157', '31', '7', '', '', '', '2001', '1', 0, 0, 0, 52, 57, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Moon, M. S., Grigal, M., & Neubert, D. (2001). High school and beyond: Students with significant disabilities complete high school through alternative programs in post-secondary settings. <I>Exceptional Parent, 31(7), </I> 52-57.', '', '', '', '', '', '2;5;6', '2;3;5;7'),
(1071, 8, 5, '', 'Mosoff, J. M., Greenholtz, J., Hurtado, T., & Jo, J, (2007). Models of Inclusive Post-Secondary Education for Young Adults with Developmental Disabilities (1st year of 3 year research project), Vancouver, BC: Canadian Council on Learning.  Retrieved  February 14, 2009, from http://www.steps-forward.org/Research.html', 0, 0, 1, 'The project described here is Phase 1 of a three part study. The overall purpose of the larger study is to develop an assessment protocol for inclusive postsecondary education in Canada. We began by examining other approaches to assessment. Three general frameworks exist: first, assessment techniques used for other programs delivered to persons with intellectual disabilities, such as person-centered planning, quality of life assessments or social role valorization. A second approach would arise from tools used to assess undergraduate education generically. This approach could be rooted in measures of student engagement. A third framework would examine inclusive post-secondary education against theories of psychosocial development in young adulthood. None of the existing approaches was entirely appropriate.\r\n\r\nThe goal of this first phase of the study was to survey the significant groups interested in inclusive post-secondary education to identify what they believed to be important in any assessment. By drawing on the three assessment traditions found in the literature and using a methodology based on grounded theory, we conducted 27 interviews with 5 different groups with direct interests in inclusive post-secondary initiatives in British Columbia: students, faculty, inclusion facilitators, campus staff, and parents. The qualitative data indicated two spheres of analysis: first, a consensus about components of successful inclusive postsecondary education, and second a tension between specific dimensions by particular groups and overarching themes that cut across particular\r\ngroups. At least three groups identified the following five components of inclusive postsecondary education: confidence, student engagement, impact on the classroom or institution, individualized paths and autonomy, and authenticity.\r\n\r\nWhile each group had its own perspective, there was a shared attention to larger concerns for persons with intellectual disabilities, most importantly the nature of support required for successful inclusion and an acknowledgement that full inclusion is a challenging, often anxiety-producing process. The study revealed some difficulties with the interview format for those students with communication challenges, an important absence of input from employers, and the necessity for improved technical resources.', '2009-05-01 14:22:33', '', 'Models of inclusive post-secondary education for young adults with developmental disabilities', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2007', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 'http://www.steps-forward.org/Research.html', 'http://www.steps-forward.org/PDF/2008%2009%20CCL%20IPSE%20Phase%20I-%20Final%20Research%20Report%20_16_.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '10', '14', 0, 0, '', '', 'Mosoff, J. M., Greenholtz, J., Hurtado, T., & Jo, J. (2007). <I>Models of inclusive post-secondary education for young adults with developmental disabilities (1st year of 3 year research project). Vancouver, BC: Canadian Council on Learning. </I> Retrieved February 14, 2009, from Steps Forward Web site: http://www.steps-forward.org/Research.html', '', '', '', '1;2;4', '2;5;9;11'),
(1072, 13, 4, '', 'RESEARCH FINDINGS BRIEF\r\nAPRIL 2000 â€¢ STUDY AREA 4a, VOLUME 7', 0, 0, 1, 'In an effort to better understand the services and accommodations that can lead to better student retention and employment options, this research finding brief describes a study of the accommodations offered to students with significant disabilities in community college settings in Massachusetts. The brief provides an overview of the research questions, research methods, findings, and implications of the study.', '2009-05-06 09:55:42', '', 'Topical review â€“ Present and promising practices in postsecondary education for students with severe cognitive disabilities', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2000', '', 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'Topical Review 2000', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Supports', 'http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase1/081-H01.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '12', 0, 0, '', '', 'National Center for the Study of Postsecondary Supports (2000). <I>Topical review â€“ Present and promising practices in postsecondary education for students with severe cognitive disabilities.</I>Retrieved June 12, 2009 from University of Hawaii Web site: http://www.rrtc.hawaii.edu/documents/products/phase1/081-H01.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2', '2;5;9'),
(1073, 2, 0, '', 'http://www.dddcec.org/publications.htm#ETDD with subscription', 0, 1, 1, 'The Point of Transition Service Integration Project was initiated in 1997 in California as a three-year model demonstration grant funded by the Department of Education. The goal of the project was to improve the level of cooperation and collaboration among public schools, the State Department of Rehabilitation, and the State Department of Developmental Services related to efforts assisting students with severe disabilities who are transitioning from school to adult life. This paper presents an overview of that project with a focus on the research questions to which it gave rise. Finally, based on findings gleaned from observation and stakeholder interviews, implications are offered and recommendations are developed to inform and improve practice.', '2009-05-06 10:36:14', '', 'Changing systems for transition: Students, families and professionals working together', 1008, 'Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities', '1547-0350', '39', '1', '', '', '', '2004', '1', 0, 0, 0, 35, 44, 0, 'Noyes, Sax 2004', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Noyes, D. A., & Sax, C. L. (2004). Changing systems for transition: Students, families and professionals working together. <I>Education and Training in Developmental Disabilities, 39(1), </I>35-44.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;4', '2;4;5'),
(1074, 2, 0, '', 'EJ517909', 0, 1, 0, 'This qualitative study examines the community college experiences of four male students, two of which are students with intellectual disabilities. Qualitative methods include â€œthickâ€œ description, triangulation, multiple coders and member checks. Themes include decisions to attend the community college, expectations of others, built-in supports, future career plans and social and interpersonal experiences.', '2009-05-06 11:07:12', '', 'The community college experience for students with and without disabilities: A viable transition outcome?', 1002, 'Career Development of Exceptional Individuals', '0885-7288', '18', '2', '', '', '', '1995', '8', 0, 0, 0, 85, 96, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Page, B., & Chadsey-Rusch, J. (1995). The community college experience for students with and without disabilities: A viable transition outcome?. <I>Career Development of Exceptional Individuals, 18(2), </I> 85-96.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '2;4;5;9'),
(1075, 2, 0, '', 'Available online with appropriate database access', 0, 1, 1, 'This article begins with a critique of the finding presented by Agran, Snow, and Swaner (1999) regarding secondary teachersâ€™ opinions about inclusion and community based instruction (CBI). The authors suggest that the aforementioned study failed to account for studentsâ€™ age as a variable affecting teachersâ€™ responses on the survey. Fisher and Sax argue that students with significant disabilities ages 14-18 are best served in inclusive secondary settings along with their age appropriate peers, while students  with significant disabilities ages 18-22 are best served in inclusive postsecondary settings.', '2009-05-06 13:14:39', '', 'Noticing the differences between secondary and postsecondary education: Extending Agran, Snow, and Swanerâ€™s discussion', 1025, 'Journal of the Association for Persons with Severe Handicaps', '', '24', '4', '', '', '', '1999', '1', 0, 0, 0, 303, 305, 0, '', '', 'http://www.ncset.hawaii.edu/institutes/mar2002/papers/pdf/Noticing%20Differences%20Between%20Secondary%20and%20Postsecondary.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '10', '22', 0, 0, 'Fisher, D., & Snow, C. (1999). Noticing the differences between secondary and postsecondary education: Extending Agran, Snow, and Swanerâ€™s discussion. <I>Journal of the Association for Persons with Severe Handicaps, 24(4), </I> 303-305.', '', 'Fisher, D., & Snow, C. (1999). <I>Noticing the differences between secondary and postsecondary education: Extending Agran, Snow, and Swanerâ€™s discussion.</I> Retrieved October 22, 2009 from University of Hawaii Web site: http://www.ncset.hawaii.edu/institutes/mar2002/papers/pdf/Noticing%20Differences%20Between%20Secondary%20and%20Postsecondary.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;4;5;6', '5;7;10'),
(1076, 1, 0, '', 'ISBN-13: 978-1-891792-90-8', 0, 1, 0, 'A guide for researchers and practitioners, this book describes how to create fully accessible college and university programs. Topics include universal design of instruction, assessments, students services, physical environments and technological environments. The text examines how to institutionalize universal design in higher education settings.', '2009-05-07 08:09:06', 'Universal design in higher education: From principles to practice', '', 0, '', 'ISBN-13: 978-1-891792-90-8', '', '', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'ISBN-13: 978-1-891792-90-8', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Burgstahler, S. E., & Cory, R. C. (2008). <I>Universal design in higher education: From principles to practice.</I> Boston: Harvard Education Press, 2008', '', 'Harvard Education Press', 'Boston', 'MA', '1', '7;8');
