(1109, 9, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'This article is a summary of a presentation given in the Division on Developmental Disabilities  Showcase Session, Research-based and Emerging Best Practices in DD/Autism: Where are We Going? at CEC in Salt Lake City, Utah. The author begins with research-based guidelines for curriculum planning, emphasizing that curriculum planning must support the transition goals of integrated community living and successful employment. Important goals of the secondary school curriculum include fostering self determination, self advocacy, and self awareness; teaching skills in the natural environment; and the use of research based strategies to promote positive social interactions (e.g. Positive Behavior Supports). The author discusses how the college or university setting provides an excellent fit for meeting the curricular and transition goals of students 18-21.', '2009-05-08 09:49:18', 'DDD Express', 'Perspectives on transition: Expanding postsecondary options for students with developmental disabilities, issues in self-determination and transition planning', 0, '', '', '17', '4', '', '', '', '2006', '1', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'DDDWinter2006', 'Division on Developmental Disabilities CEC', 'http://www.dddcec.org/ETMRDDV/DDDexpress/DDDWinter2006.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '18', 0, 0, '', '', 'Zager, D. (2006). Perspectives on transition: Expanding postsecondary options for students with developmental disabilities, issues in self-determination and transition planning.<I>DDD Express 17(4)</I> Retrieved from http://www.dddcec.org/ETMRDDV/DDDexpress/DDDWinter2006.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;5;6', '4;5;6;7;9;11;12'),
(1110, 9, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'This article discusses the Pace Campus-Based Inclusion Program for Students with Autism and Developmental Disabilities and relates the experiences of the author, participating faculty and students.', '2009-05-08 09:56:48', 'The Education Forum', 'The right place at the right time: The Pace campus-based inclusion program\r\nfor students with autism and developmental disabilities', 0, '', '', '3', '8', '', '', '', '2006', '1', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 1, 'nycNewsletterNovember2006', 'Pace University', 'http://www.pace.edu/emplibrary/nycNewsletterNovember2006.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '16', 0, 0, '', '', 'Zager, D. (2006). The right place at the right time: The Pace campus-based inclusion program\r\nfor students with autism and developmental disabilities. <I>The Education Forum 3(8)</I> Retrieved from http://www.pace.edu/emplibrary/nycNewsletterNovember2006.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '4;5;6;7;9'),
(1111, 8, 6, '', 'Hart, D. & Grigal, M. (2004). Individual support to increase access to an inclusive college experience for students with intellectual disabilities [online module]. College Park, MD: University of Maryland, Department of Special Education. Available from On-Campus Outreach, http://www.education.umd.edu/oco/', 0, 1, 1, 'The purpose of this online training module is to provide guidance on developing an Individual Support Model (ISM) to increase access to inclusive college experiences and to improve chances for the success of students with intellectual disabilities. An ISM approach provides students with individualized services and supports (e.g., educational coach, tutor, technology, natural supports) in college courses, certificate programs, internships, and/or degree programs. This module does not offer a recipe for developing an ISM but presents some of the key elements, strategies, and lessons learned from seven years of work on development of the model. The ISM should reflect the community and the needs of its members and, therefore, will look different in different situations. This online training module will walk the reader through five major steps in the ISM process, as it applies to students with intellectual disabilities who have postsecondary education as a goal. Each step will include an introduction, specific implementation strategies, participant outcomes, and additional information and resources.', '2009-05-08 10:11:50', 'On-campus outreach online training modules:', 'Individual support to increase access to an inclusive college experience for students with intellectual disabilities [online module].', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2004', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 'University of Maryland OCO', 'http://www.education.umd.edu/oco/training/oco_training_modules/IndividualSupports/start.html', '', '', '', '', '2009', '6', '18', 0, 0, '', '', 'Hart, D., & Grigal, M. (2004). Individual support to increase access to an inclusive college experience for students with intellectual disabilities [online module]. College Park, MD: University of Maryland, Department of Special Education. Available from On-Campus Outreach, http://www.education.umd.edu/oco/training/oco_training_modules/IndividualSupports/start.html', '', '', '', '', ''),
(1115, 1, 0, '3', 'ISBN: 978-1-84855-310-1', 0, 0, 0, 'This chapter examines the myriad new provisions in HEOA intended to improve access to higher education for students with disabilities as well as HEOAâ€™s provisions related to preparing teachers to effectively instruct students with disabilities in the K-12 environment. Multiple new provisions reflect an invigorated commitment to developing a workforce for todayâ€™s schools â€“ schools with unprecedented diversity â€“ and to addressing the critical teacher shortages, including special education. This chapter is organized around three themes: access to higher education for students with disabilities, investing in the capacity of higher education to serve students with disabilities, and strengthening the preparation of teachers of students with disabilities, including accountability for this preparation.', '2009-11-10 08:50:56', 'Policy and Practice Volume 22 of the book series: Advances in Learning and Behavioral Disabilities', 'Increasing access to higher education for students with disabilities and strengthening the preparation of professionals who instruct them: The Higher Education Opportunity Act of 2008', 0, '', '', '22', '', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 189, 225, 0, 'West chapter 2009', '', 'http://www.emeraldinsight.com/Insight/viewContentItem.do;jsessionid=F5625BF27E0EFF21B8510E1B4F887E9F?contentType=Book&contentId=1812032', 'doi:10.1108', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'West, J. (2009). <I>Policy and Practice Volume 22 of the book series: Advances in Learning and Behavioral Disabilities</I>. Bingley: UK: Emerald Publishing.', '', 'Emerald Publishing', 'Bingley: UK', '', '1;2;4', '5;6;7;10;11'),
(1116, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'This article reports the results of a study investigating special educatorsâ€™ perceptions of, and practices to promote self-determination among students with significant disabilities. The authors surveyed the perceptions of special educators on the benefits of self-determination, the characteristics associated with it, and the strategies used to achieve it.  Although teachers reported numerous benefits of instruction in self-determination, few educators included self-determination skills in IEPs.  The implications of the studyâ€™s findings are discussed.', '2009-11-11 08:00:29', '', 'Teacher perceptions of self-determination: Benefits, characteristics, strategies', 1009, 'Education and Training in Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities', '', '34', '', '', '', '', '1999', '', 0, 0, 0, 293, 301, 0, 'Agran, Snow, Swaner 1999', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2009', '9', '9', 1, 0, 'Agran, M., Snow, C., & Swaner, J. (1999). Teacher perceptions of self-determination: Benefits, characteristics, strategies. <I>Education and Training in Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities, 34(3), </I> 293-301.', '', '', '', '', '', '2', '12'),
(1117, 2, 0, '', 'Originally in Education and Training of the Mentally Retarded', 0, 1, 0, 'This article reports on an experimental clerical training program at Ferris State College designed to prepare young women with intellectual disabilities for employment in small offices, duplicating rooms or mailrooms.  The authors found that participants learned typing, filing, and duplicator machine operation in the same manner as peers without disabilities.  Tested intelligence and reading scores were not correlated with participantsâ€™ ability to learn basic vocational skills.', '2009-11-11 08:42:53', '', 'Clerical training for the mentally retarded on a college campus', 1009, 'Education and Training in Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities', '', '7', '', '', '', '', '1972', '', 0, 0, 0, 135, 140, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 1, 0, 'Baxter, J. M. (1972). Clerical training for the mentally retarded on a college campus. <I>Education and Training in Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities, 7(3), </I> 135-140.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;3', '5;11'),
(1118, 1, 0, '3', '', 0, 1, 0, 'This chapter discusses Universal Course Design (UCD) as a professional development strategy that allows university and college instructors to effectively reach all learners. The goal of UDC is to prepare faculty to increase college studentsâ€™ access to  curriculum, instruction, assessment, and the learning environment. The chapter defines UCD and contrasts UCD with Universal Design for Learning (UDL) and Universal Design of Instruction (UDI). Central to implementing UCD is the UCD team. The purposes, membership and activities of a UCD team is provided, including examples of how the UCD team supported teachers to apply UCD strategies in their classrooms. The chapter closes with recommendations on how to sustain UCD on a college campus, and identifies five elements that lead to UCD sustainability: the activities of a UCD team, initiating UCD from within the campus community, actively seeking studentâ€™s insights, and representing UDC as a strategy that improves instruction for all students - including students with disabilities.', '2009-11-11 08:48:48', 'Universal design in higher education', 'Universal course design: A model for professional development', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', '', 'Library ISBN: 978-1-891792-91-5', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Behling, K., & Hart, D. (2008). Universal course design: A model for professional development. In S.E. Burgstahler & R.C. Cory (Eds.),<I>Universal design in higher education</I> (pp. 109-125). Cambridge, MA: Harvard Education Press.', '', 'Harvard Education Press', 'Cambridge', 'MA', '1', '8'),
(1119, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'The author begins this article with a metaphor in which the scarecrow in the Wizard of Oz is compared to students with intellectual disabilities.  In the Wizard of Oz, the scarecrow is told by many that he does not have a brain, yet throughout the journey to OZ he demonstrates his wisdom and intelligence.  Created in 1974 the College of Living is a program is a program of Metropolitan State College in Denver.  The program serves students with intellectual disabilities.  Classes were taught by volunteer Metropolitan State college students, and according to the author, the life skills curriculum was driven by the interests and ideas of the College of Living students. Beginning with just five students in 1974, by 1977 the College of Living served 200 students, providing courses taught by 40 volunteer college students.', '2009-11-11 08:55:43', '', 'Scarecrows as students at Coloradoâ€™s College for Living', 1038, 'Phi Delta Kappan', '', '59', '', '', '', '', '1977', '', 0, 0, 0, 11, 17, 1, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Dahms, A. M., Ackler, E. J., & Aandahl, V. S. (1977). Scarecrows as students at Coloradoâ€™s College for Living. <I>Phi Delta Kappan, 59, </I> 11-17.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;6', '5;7;9'),
(1120, 2, 0, '', 'http://cde.sagepub.com/', 0, 1, 1, 'The purpose of this article is to identify legal issues concerning the transition planning process through a qualitative analysis of administrative and judicial decisions addressing transition services for students with disabilities. The issues that emerged from the analysis were categorized into five prevalent themes: agency contacts, student involvement, individualization of the transition plan, district obligations, and appropriateness of the transition plan. The themes included both procedural and substantive components. Changes in the newly reauthorized Individuals with Disabilities Education Act are discussed, and implications for policy and practice are presented. [journal]\r\n\r\nThe study used purposive sampling for this policy analysis, and selected 36 published decisions, 31 of which were state-level administrative decisions and five of which were district court rulings. The appendix includes a summary of the cases in the study. Of these cases, the students primary disability included intellectual disabilities (n=8), learning disabilities (n = 5), emotional or behavioral disorders (n = 4), autism or Asperger syndrome (n = 4), multiple disabilities (n = 4), physical disabilities (n = 3), other health impaired (n = 2), attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (n = 2), traumatic brain injury (n = 1), and other or unspecified (n =3).', '2009-11-11 09:17:13', '', 'Issues in transition planning: Legal decisions', 1002, 'Career Development for Exceptional Individuals', '', '29', '1', '', '', '', '2006', '', 0, 0, 0, 28, 47, 0, 'Etscheidt 2006', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Etscheidt, S. (2006). Issues in transition planning: Legal decisions. <I>Career Development for Exceptional Individuals, 29(1), </I> 28-47.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;6', '4;5'),
(1121, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'A survey was conducted with 234 parents of secondary-level students with high- and low-incidence disabilities in two urban school systems about the importance of secondary instructional domains and transition planning and their post-school expectations for their son or daughter. Significant differences were found between parents of students with high- and low-incidence disabilities in the values they placed on instructional domains and transition planning areas, their desired independent living situations, and their post-school expectations for education and employment for their son or daughter. Implications for practice and research are discussed. [journalâ€™s abstract]', '2009-11-11 09:23:02', '', 'Parentsâ€™ in-school values and post-school expectations for transition-aged youth with disabilities', 1002, 'Career Development for Exceptional Individuals', '', '27', '1', '', '', '', '2004', '', 0, 0, 0, 65, 86, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Grigal, M., & Neubert, D. (2004). Parentsâ€™ in-school values and post-school expectations for transition-aged youth with disabilities. <I>Career Development for Exceptional Individuals, 27(1), </I> 65-86.', '', '', '', '', '', '2;6', '4;5'),
(1122, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'This article discusses a campus-based transition program for youth with mild disabilities, located at the William Patterson College campus.  The LINK program provided transition services to 22 high school graduates with mild disabilities, six of whom were classified as â€œmild mental retardationâ€.  Program staff were peer mentors who were students matriculated at the college. Program activities included instruction in social competence, social and recreational activities, and paid part-time employment experiences. Courses were segregated, non-credit bearing and unrelated to the general college curriculum.  The author suggests that the positive impact of the program would be enhanced if transition services were offered while students were still in high school.', '2009-11-11 09:26:20', '', 'LINK: A campus-based transition program for non-college bound youth with mild disabilities', 1002, 'Career Development for Exceptional Individuals', '', '16', '1', '', '', '', '1993', '', 0, 0, 0, 75, 84, 0, 'Goldstein 1993', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Goldstein, M. T. (1993). LINK: A campus-based transition program for non-college bound youth with mild disabilities. <I>Career Development for Exceptional Individuals, 16(1), </I> 75-84.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;6', '4;5;7;9;11'),
(1124, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'A survey of 136 community colleges showed that 37.5% served mentally retarded students, in programs designed specifically for those students or adapted to accommodate their needs. A discussion of the types of services provided, plans to expand or develop new services, special faculty training, policies, and attitudes is included.', '2009-11-11 09:47:24', '', 'Accommodation of adults who are mentally retarded in community colleges: A national study', 1009, 'Education and Training in Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities', '', '22', '4', '', '', '', '1987', '', 0, 0, 0, 262, 267, 0, 'McAfee, Sheeler 1987', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'McAfee, J. K., & Sheeler, M. C. (1987). Accommodation of adults who are mentally retarded in community colleges: A national study. <I>Education and Training in Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities, 22(4), </I> 262-267.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;6', '5;7'),
(1125, 1, 0, '3', '', 0, 1, 0, 'In this chapter, the authors provide a conceptual framework for preparing students with severe disabilities for meaningful employment. The authors  suggest that vocational preparation must be integrated within a larger scope of supporting the transition from adolescence to adulthood.  The chapter provides a definition of transition and identifies the characteristics of effective vocational preparation and transition programs for students with severe disabilities. Themes explored include: local collaboration among schools, community agencies, businesses and families; studentsâ€™ choice, preferences, and interests; self-determination; inclusion; dual enrollment in high school and postsecondary education; interagency collaboration through statewide, local and individual student transition teams; paid employment; longitudinal instruction across grades and settings; and establishing community-based training sites and designing instructional programs for teaching job related skills; compliance with labor laws; assistive technology for student with physical disabilities; social security benefits and work incentives; secondary and postsecondary service alignment and longitudinal supports. The authors illustrate how to plan and implement effective transition activities, using examples from two students with intellectual disabilities (Jane and Heather). Includes eight tables and nine figures.', '2009-11-11 09:50:28', 'Instruction of students with severe disabilities', 'Vocational preparation and transition', 0, '', '', '', '', '5', '', '', '2000', '', 0, 0, 0, 591, 628, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Moon, M.S., & Inge, K.V. (2000). Vocational preparation and transition. In M. Snell & F. Brown (Eds.), <I>Instruction of students with severe disabilities</I> (5th ed., pp. 591â€“628). Upper Saddle River, NJ: Merrill.', '', 'Merrill', 'Upper Saddle River', 'NJ', '1;2;3;6', '1;2;5;7;9;11;12'),
(1126, 1, 0, '3', '', 0, 1, 0, 'Reflecting on the differences in the ways schools support students with and without disabilities to dream about and plan for their futures, this chapter presents a critique of the transition construct. The authors suggest that the transition construct creates as segregated graduation and career planning process for students with disabilities, and that an alternative approach is needed and possible.  The chapter includes a Graduation Planning Checklist, and provides an example of how the Graduation Planning Checklist may be used to support a high school student with significant disabilities. The chapter closes with a discussion of alternatives to a separate futures planning process for students with disabilities.', '2009-11-11 09:56:16', 'Restructuring high schools for all students: Taking students to the next level', 'Transition or graduation? Supporting all students to plan for the future', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1998', '', 0, 0, 0, 234, 259, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, '', 'Tashie, C., Malloy, J.M., & Lichtenstein, S.J. (1998). Transition or graduation? Supporting all students to plan for the future. In C.J. Jorgensen (Ed.), <I>Restructuring high schools for all students: Taking students to the next level. </I> (pp. 234â€“259). Baltimore: Brookes Publishing Co.', '', 'Brookes Publishing Co', 'Baltimore', 'MD', '2;6', '4;5'),
(1127, 14, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'This resource is useful for individuals and programs interested in transition program development and/or improvement. In light of the expanding number and diversity of postsecondary and transition programs for youth with intellectual disabilities, determining the quality of these services and resulting student outcomes is essential. This document suggests evidence based, objective measures that can be used design, implement, evaluate, and/or expand high quality postsecondary and transition programs for youth with intellectual disabilities. The foundation for each measure of program quality are transition practices identified as effective in the literature on transition as well as by the National Alliance for Secondary Education and Transition (NASET). The user friendly document includes a four point rating scale that can be used to self-assess the quality of program services. Domains of evaluation include student outcomes, student activities, policies and practices and administration.', '2009-11-11 10:03:45', '', 'Suggested promising practices for postsecondary education services for students with intellectual disabilities', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Grigal, Hart 2008', 'Transition to College', 'http://www.transitiontocollege.net/percpubs/PromisingPractices2008.pdf', '', '', '', '', '2009', '9', '22', 0, 0, '', '', 'Grigal, M. & Hart, D. (2008). Suggested promising practices for postsecondary education services for students with intellectual disabilities. Rockville, MD: Transcen Inc. Retrieved October 7, 2009 from http://www.transitiontocollege.net/percpubs/PromisingPractices2008.pdf', 'Transcen Inc.', 'Rockville', 'MD', '1;2;4;6', '2;4;5;8;11;12'),
(1129, 2, 9, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'Some universities and colleges across the country are creating opportunities for young adults with significant disabilities to meaninfully participate in postsecondary education. Students with significant disabilities are now attending college classes with their peers without disabilities either during or after high school. In this qualitative study, the authors investigated two programs in Central New York that support students with significant disabilities to attend college classes in inclusive settings.  The authors interviewed stakeholders and asked questions focused on the benefits of and obstacles to program implementation.  While respondents identified benefits to students, classmates and professors, obstacles were intitutional, logistical and attitudinal in nature. Inplications of the study''s findings are discussed.', '2009-11-17 12:04:00', '', 'Relentless optimism: Inclusive postsecondary opportunities for students with significant disabilities', 1022, 'Journal of Postsecondary Education and Disability', '', '22', '2', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 88, 105, 0, 'Causton-Theoharis, Ashby, DeClouette 2009', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Causton-Theoharis, J., Ashby, C., & Declouette, N. (2009). Relentless optimism: Inclusive postsecondary opportunities for students with significant disabilities.  <I>Journal of Postsecondary Education and Disabilities, 22(2),</I> 88-105.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;4;6', '1;2;4;5;6;7;9'),
(1130, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 1, 'Brief article chronicles the use of peer mentors at the College of New Jerseyâ€™s College and Community Studies Program.', '2009-11-18 10:23:21', '', 'The use of peer mentors to facilitate the inclusion of youth with Intellectual Disabilities and Developmental Disabilities in post-secondary education', 1039, 'NADD Bulletin, The', '', '12', '5', '', '', '', '2009', '1', 0, 0, 0, 93, 87, 0, '', 'NADD Web site', 'http://www.thenadd.org/cgi-bin/checkmember.pl?page=pages/membership/bulletins/v12n5a2', 'ISSN: 1065-2574', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Blumberg, R., & Daley, R. (2009). The use of peer mentors to facilitate the inclusion of youth with intellectual disabilities and developmental disabilities in post-secondary education. <I>NADD Bulletin, The, 12(5), </I> 93-87.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '5;7;9'),
(1131, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 'This article describes how 12 pre-service teachers who participated in an inclusive liberal learning understood their experience. The analysis of interviews with these pre-service teachers suggests that they emerged from the course with a commitment to the idea that students with intellectual disabilities have a right to a challenging liberal education. Most emerged with a stronger commitment to inclusive teaching practice and felt that the use of small group activities and discussions was the best way to build classroom community, create relationships among participants, and maximize learning. All of the interviewed pre-service teachers considered this course a positive academic experience.', '2009-11-18 11:08:12', '', 'The impact of a college course where pre-service teachers and peers with intellectual disabilities study together', 1040, 'Teacher Education and Special Education', '', '32', '4', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 351, 364, 0, 'Carroll, Petroff, Blumberg 2009', '', '', 'DOI: 10.1177/0888406409346145', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Carroll, S., Petroff, J., & Blumberg, R. (2009). The impact of a college course where pre-service teachers and peers with intellectual disabilities study together. <I>Teacher Education and Special Education, 32(4), </I> 351-364.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;3;4;6', '2;4;5;7;9'),
(1132, 2, 0, '', 'EJ821999', 0, 0, 0, 'Post-secondary education for youth with Intellectual Disabilities is an emerging area of research. Although there has been increasing interest and recent programme development in this area, there is little research that explores benefits of liberal learning for these students. This paper describes the experiences of three college faculty who designed inclusive courses for youth with Intellectual Disabilities, grounded in liberal learning, at a mid-sized four-year college, in New Jersey. Each professor describes their approach to course design, instruction and evaluation of student learning. Implications for programme design and instruction are discussed, as well as demonstrated benefits for students with Intellectual Disabilities.', '2009-11-18 11:21:44', '', 'Career and community studies: an inclusive liberal arts programme for youth with Intellectual Disabilities', 1041, 'International Journal of Inclusive Education', '', '12', '5-6', '', '', '', '2008', '9', 0, 0, 0, 621, 637, 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Blumberg, R., Carroll, S., & Petroff, J. (2008). Career and community studies: an inclusive liberal arts programme for youth with Intellectual Disabilities. <I>International Journal of Inclusive Education, 12(5-6), </I> 621-637.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;3;4;6', '2;4;5;7;9'),
(1133, 2, 0, '', 'Excerpted from: Changes Over Time in the Early Postschool Outcomes of Youth with Disabilities. A Report of Findings from the National Longitudinal Transition Study (NLTS) and the National Longitudinal Transition Study-2 (NLTS2).', 0, 1, 0, 'Two studies by the U.S. Department of Education provide documentation of changes experienced since the mid 1980s by secondary school students with disabilities as they transition to young adulthood. Purpose: To assess change between 1987 and 2003 in the early postschool outcomes (i.e. postsecondary enrollment, employment, engagement in the community, living arrangements, and social involvement) of youth with disabilities. Changes also are described for youth with disabilities who differed in their school-exit status, age, gender, household income, and race/ethnicity. Findings: By 2003 there were significant increases in youth with disabilities'' postsecondary education enrollment and employment rates. There also was an increase in participation in organized community groups. Despite the positive changes, other changes were disconcerting: the sizable increase in the proportion of youth with disabilities who had been fired from a job or arrested. In addition, there was no real change in earnings over time when wages were adjusted for inflation. There were differential changes in outcomes across disability categories, continued limitations for youth from households with lower income, and decreasing but persistent racial/ethnic differences. Conclusion: The age groups included in NLTS and NLTS2 and the timing of data collection in the two studies permit one more comparison between youth with disabilities represented in the two studies--when youth were ages 18 through 21 and had been out of high school up to 4 years. Analyses of those cohorts, to be presented in future reports, will reveal the ways in which the changes in the early postschool outcomes of youth with disabilities documented in this report evolve as youth continue into early adulthood.', '2010-04-19 11:22:11', '', 'Chapter 4: Changes in Postsecondary Education Participation of Youth with Disabilities', 1018, 'Journal for Vocational Special Needs Education, The', '', '27', '2', '', '', '', '2005', '', 0, 0, 0, 30, 38, 0, 'Newman 2005', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Newman, L. (2005). Chapter 4: Changes in Postsecondary Education Participation of Youth with Disabilities. <I>Journal for Vocational Special Needs Education, The, 27(2), </I> 30-38.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '2;4;5;7;10;11'),
(1134, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'The amendments to the Individuals with Disabilities Education Improvement Act (IDEIA) in 2004 reiterate the significance of producing real postsecondary education, employment, and independent living outcomes. However, current employment data continue to show widespread unemployment and very limited access to inclusive community environments and services for adults with severe intellectual disabilities. On the contrary, data from the Transition\r\nService Integration Model (N. J. Certo et al, 2003) demonstrate that these recalcitrant problems could be attenuated if two changes are implemented: the transition from school to adulthood components of IDEIA be strengthened to explicitly authorize school districts to subcontract with appropriate private agencies at the point of transition to produce direct-hire, individualized employment and adult living outcomes and that the federal government amend the\r\nDevelopmental Disabilities Assistance and Bill of Rights Act to provide an entitlement to long-term support, creating a service system which parallels the functions of IDEIA after school exit.', '2010-04-19 13:22:28', '', 'Seamless Transition and Long-Term Support for Individuals With Severe Intellectual Disabilities', 1029, 'Research and Practice for Persons with Severe Disabilities', '', '33', '3', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 85, 95, 0, 'Certo.Luecking.Murphy.Brown.Courey.Belanger.2009', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Certo, N., Luecking, R., Murphy, S., Brown, L., Courey, S., & Belanger, D. (2008). Seamless Transition and Long-Term Support for Individuals With Severe Intellectual Disabilities. <I>Research and Practice for Persons with Severe Disabilities, 33(3), </I> 85-95.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4', '4;5;7;10'),
(1135, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'This introduction discusses various reports published within the special issue of Exceptionality focused on transition, including the article about postsecondary education services to students with disabilities and another on postsecondary education transition option for youth with intellectual disabilities.', '2010-04-19 13:50:44', '', 'Transition to Postsecondary Education', 1042, 'Exceptionality', '', '16', '', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 175, 177, 0, 'deFur.2008.TransitionOutcomes', '', '', '10.1080/09362830802412125', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'deFur, S. (2008). Transition to Postsecondary Education. <I>Exceptionality, 16, </I> 175-177.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4', '4;5'),
(1136, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'Forces including legislation, policy, standards-based educational reforms, and changing economic and social conditions have dramatically altered the conversation and practices around postsecondary transition. This article traces the development of postsecondary transition as it is reflected in the professional literature and federal legislation since 1975. Over time, increasing expectations, access, and outcomes for students with disabilities are moving the goals for transition toward postsecondary education and lifelong learning to help graduates achieve continuing success in employment and adult life.', '2010-04-20 11:49:31', '', 'The Evolution Toward Lifelong Learning as a Critical Transition Outcome for the 21st Century', 1042, 'Exceptionality', '', '16', '4', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 178, 191, 0, 'deFur & Korinek 2008', '', '', '10.1080/09362830802412158', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'deFur, S., & Korinek, L. (2008). The Evolution Toward Lifelong Learning as a Critical Transition Outcome for the 21st Century. <I>Exceptionality, 16(4), </I> 178-191.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;4;5;6', '4;5;7;10'),
(1137, 2, 0, '', 'This is a preprint of an article submitted for consideration in the Reference Librarian Â© 2009 copyright Taylor & Francis; Reference Librarian is available online at informaworldTM', 0, 1, 1, 'Syracuse University Library and Access partnered to provide library orientations to six Syracuse University students who have developmental disabilities. Access is a service that supports college course attendance for students who have developmental or cognitive disabilities. Students with developmental disabilities are being included in college life more and more. As this occurs, academic libraries will be providing more services to this population. We hope Syracuse Universityâ€™s experience will be useful for other libraries to build on as they develop services. Additionally, we discuss opportunities to improve services for all students by focusing on students with developmental disabilities.', '2010-04-20 15:18:11', '', 'Academic Library Services for Users with Developmental Disabilities: Partnership of Access and Syracuse University Library', 1043, 'The Reference Librarian', '', '50', '3', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 276, 287, 0, 'mulliken, atkins 2009', 'Social Science Research Network', 'http://ssrn.com/abstract=1398085', '10.1080/02763870902873461', '', '', '', '2010', '4', '22', 0, 0, 'Mulliken, A., & Atkins, A. (2009). Academic Library Services for Users with Developmental Disabilities: Partnership of Access and Syracuse University Library. <I>The Reference Librarian, 50(3), </I> 276-287.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;5', '5;7'),
(1138, 13, 0, '', 'maybe delete duplicate?', 0, 0, 1, 'One role of Vocational Rehabilitation is to support postsecondary education in accordance with studentâ€™s Individualized Plans for Employment (IPE). This data note compares the employment outcomes of youth with intellectual disabilities who did and who did not receive postsecondary educational supports as a part of their IPEs.  Data analysis revealed that youth who participated in postsecondary education were 26% more likely to exit the VR program with employment, and their weekly wage earning were 73% higher than those who had no postsecondary education experiences.  This study suggests that postsecondary education for persons with intellectual disabilities is indeed a promising practice.', '2010-04-22 14:51:48', '', 'Postsecondary Education and Employment Outcomes for Youth with Intellectual Disabilities', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Migliore.Butterworth.2009', 'StateData.info', 'http://www.statedata.info/datanotes/datanote.php?article_id=267', '', '', '', '', '2010', '4', '22', 0, 0, '', '', 'Migliore, A., & Butterworth, J. (2009). Postsecondary education and employment outcomes for youth with intellectual disabilities.<I>Data Note No. 21, 2009. </I> Retrieved April 22, 2010, from StateData.info Web site: http://www.statedata.info/datanotes/datanote.php?article_id=267', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '4;5;7;11'),
(1139, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'Students with intellectual disabilities aged 18â€“21 are increasingly receiving transition services on college campuses during the last years of public schooling. These students may attend college courses, work in the community, access community recreational activities, and engage in age-appropriate experiences with peers without disabilities. However, there is little research that documents the types of practices included, the perspectives of consumers, or the outcomes of these transition services. Results from this case study depict how one public school program on a community college campus incorporated recommended transition practices and how students with intellectual disabilities and their families perceived these practices.', '2010-04-23 15:16:18', '', 'Transition Services for Students with Intellectual Disabilities: A Case Study of a Public School Program on a Community College Campus', 1042, 'Exceptionality', '', '16', '4', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 220, 234, 0, 'Neubert and Redd 2008', '', '', '10.1080/09362830802412265', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Neubert, D., & Redd, V. (2008). Transition Services for Students with Intellectual Disabilities: A Case Study of a Public School Program on a Community College Campus. <I>Exceptionality, 16(4), </I> 220-234.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '2;4;5;7;11;12'),
(1140, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'While supported employment has made significant gains since its formal introduction in 1984 (P.L. 98-527), segregated services continue to outpace the growth of supported employment. We discuss these and other important trends in this article, and conclude with recommendations that include (1) ensuring that all young adults leave high school competitively used or admitted to postsecondary education by age 18 and (2) that high schools coordinate post-placement follow-up for 3 years following employment or enrollment in postsecondary education. These recommendations are made because although current research suggests practices exist to employ persons with severe disabilities outside sheltered workshops and adult day care centers, these programs continue to grow at an alarming rate. In fact, the growth of supported employment has all but stalled since 2000. Diverting people and resources at the juncture between high school preparation and assuming adult roles such as employment appears to be a more realistic plan to promote integrated services over the foreseeable future.', '2010-05-04 11:31:20', '', 'Adult Day Programs Versus Supported Employment (1988-2002): Spending and Service Practices of Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities State Agencies', 1029, 'Research and Practice for Persons with Severe Disabilities', '', '29', '4', '', '', '', '2004', '', 0, 0, 0, 237, 242, 0, 'Rusch.Braddock.2004.Adult Day v. SE.Background info', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Rusch, F., & Braddock, D. (2004). Adult Day Programs Versus Supported Employment (1988-2002): Spending and Service Practices of Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities State Agencies. <I>Research and Practice for Persons with Severe Disabilities, 29(4), </I> 237-242.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '2;3;5;11'),
(1141, 4, 6, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'The National Longitudinal  Transition Study-2 (NLTS2) is a 10-year-long study of the characteristics, experiences, and outcomes of a nationally representative sample of youth with  disabilities who were 13 to 16 years  old and receiving special education services in grade 7 or above, under the Individuals With Disabilities  Education Act (IDEA) in the 2000-2001 school year. NLTS2 findings generalize to youth  with disabilities nationally and to youth in each of the 12 federal special education disability categories in use for students in the NLTS2 age range. The study  is designed to collect data on sample members from  multiple sources in five waves, beginning in 2001 and ending in 2009. Much of the information reported in this document comes from  youth with disabilities  in the form of responses to either a telephone interview or a self-administered mail survey with a subset of key items from the telephone interview. Data for youth who were reported by parents to be unable to respond to an interview or complete a questionnaire or who did not respond to interview or survey attempts were provided by parents. Data from the three sources were combined for these analyses and subsetted to include only data for out-of-high  school youth. This report  is organized to provide information on out-of-high  school youth with  disabilities in several key domains, including: (1) Postsecondary education enrollment and educational experiences, such as major field of study and support services received; (2) Employment status and characteristics of youth''s current or most recent job; (3) Productive engagement in school, work, or preparation for work; (4) Residential independence; the prevalence of marriage, parenting, and sexual behavior; and aspects of their financial independence; and (5) Social and community involvement, including friendship activities and community participation in both positive and negative ways. Comparisons are made between experiences across different disability categories and demographic groups, and, when data are available, with those of youth  in the general population. NLTS2 will continue to follow the lives of youth with  disabilities as they age, which will provide information to examine how post-high  school outcomes might evolve over time. Two appendixes are included: (1) NLTS2 Sampling, Data Collection, and Analysis Procedures; and (2) Additional Analyses. (Chapters and appendixes are footnoted individually. References provided by report and individual appendix. Contains 41 figures and 81 tables.)', '2010-05-10 15:01:09', '', 'The Post-High School Outcomes of Youth With Disabilities up to 4 Years After High School: A Report From the National Longitudinal Transition Study-2 (NLTS2) NCSER', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'nlts2_report_2009_04_complete', 'Institute of Education Sciences', 'http://ies.ed.gov/ncser/pdf/20093017.pdf', '', '', '4', '', '2010', '5', '10', 0, 0, '', '', 'Newman, L., Wagner, M., Cameto, R., & Knokey, A. (2009). <I>The Post-High School Outcomes of Youth With Disabilities up to 4 Years After High School: A Report From the National Longitudinal Transition Study-2 (NLTS2).</I> Retrieved May 10, 2010, from Institute of Education Sciences Web site: http://ies.ed.gov/ncser/pdf/20093017.pdf', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '2;4;5;7;11'),
(1142, 9, 4, '', '', 0, 1, 1, 'Higher Education Opportunity Act (enacted August 14, 2008, reauthorizes the Higher Education Act of 1965) improves access to PSE for students with intellectual disabilities, particularly through provisions that address financial aid and create a new model demonstration program and coordinating center for students with intellectual disabilities.', '2010-08-03 14:35:26', 'Think College Policy Brief', 'Overview of the Federal Higher Education Opportunity Act Reauthorization', 0, '', '', '', '1', '', '', '', '2009', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Lee 2009, HEAC_Overview', 'Think College', 'http://thinkcollege.net/publications', '', '', '', '', '2010', '7', '28', 0, 0, '', '', 'Lee, S. (2009). Overview of the Federal Higher Education Opportunity Act Reauthorization. <I>Think College Policy Brief (1)</I> Retrieved from http://thinkcollege.net/publications', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '2;3;4;5;10'),
(1143, 2, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 0, 'Discusses transition services for youth with severe disabilities to employment or further education, arguing for the need to work on new legislation that focuses on continued coordination supporting youth beyond high school participation rather than continuing to discuss "valued outcomes." Calls for accountability of high school and adult service agencies in the transition process for outcomes that reflect societal values. Legislation promoting the following is needed: (a) teaching and promoting student participation in decisions about jobs or additional schooling; b) schools being held accountable for placing students in these jobs or PSE institutions; and c) schools orchestrating the coordinated services that are important to ensure long-term employment.', '2010-08-03 14:50:50', '', 'When Will Our Values Finally Result in the Creation of New Pathways for Change--Change That We Can Believe In?', 1029, 'Research and Practice for Persons with Severe Disabilities', '', '33', '3', '', '', '', '2008', '', 0, 0, 0, 96, 97, 0, 'Rusch & Wolfe 2008', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 'Rusch, F., & Wolfe, P. (2008). When Will Our Values Finally Result in the Creation of New Pathways for Change--Change That We Can Believe In?. <I>Research and Practice for Persons with Severe Disabilities, 33(3), </I> 96-97.', '', '', '', '', '', '1;2;3;4;5;6', '2;4;10'),
(1144, 5, 0, '', '', 0, 1, 1, '19-year-old Katie Apostolides was diagnosed with the severest form of Down syndrome when she was born. Article discusses the experience of parents, other supports, Katie''s mainstream high school activities and her plans to attend college.', '2010-08-03 15:00:49', 'Post-Gazette', 'Determined teen overcomes obstacles to create a life she loves', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2002', '12', 24, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Munroe 2002 K. Apostilides', 'Post-Gazette', 'http://www.post-gazette.com/neigh_north/20021224ncoverp2.asp', '', '', '', '', '2010', '8', '3', 0, 0, '', '', 'Munroe, C. (2002, December 24). Determined teen overcomes obstacles to create a life she loves. <I>Post-Gazette.</I> Retrieved from http://www.post-gazette.com/neigh_north/20021224ncoverp2.asp', '', 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', '1;2;5;6', '5'),
(1145, 8, 0, '', 'A thesis by Robin E. Swift, University of Calgary, 88 pages', 0, 1, 1, 'This study is a phenomenological exploration of the university experiences of students enrolled in an Inclusive Postsecondary Education (IPSE) program. The enquiry centered on the question: What is the student''s perspective of his or her university experience while attending an IPSE program? Data was analyzed thematically and this resulted in the isolation of five themes: fear and hanging on, "I can make friends, too," the road to belonging, "I have choices," and better hopes and dreams. A main finding was that students were able to give trustworthy accounts of their university experiences. Another major finding was that the university appeared to serve as a transitioning environment for these students by fostering learning, identity development, and maturity, preparing them for the adult world of work. A limitation noted with the study was that it lacked a series of interviews that may have been helpful in establishing rapport and minimizing problems relating to the participants'' memory deficits. Recommendations for future research are provided in the discussion.', '2010-08-05 13:14:29', 'Attending an inclusive post-secondary education setting: the perspectives of students with significant intellectual disabilities', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2001', '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Robyn_Swift_Thesis_on_IPSE', 'University of Calgary Institutional Repository', 'http://dspace1.acs.ucalgary.ca/handle/1880/41243', '', '', '', '', '2010', '8', '3', 0, 0, '', '', 'Swift, Robin E. (2001). <I>Attending an inclusive post-secondary education setting: the perspectives of students with significant intellectual disabilities</I> (Master''s thesis). Retrieved from http://dspace1.acs.ucalgary.ca/handle/1880/41243', '', '', '', '1;2;5;6', '2;4;5');
